WEBVTT

1
00:00:37.371 --> 00:00:39.665
My name's Paul Greengrass...

2
00:00:39.873 --> 00:00:44.169
...and this is the director's commentary
for <i>Captain Phillips.</i>

3
00:00:45.963 --> 00:00:50.842
The story starts in a small
farming community. Underhill. Vermont...

4
00:00:52.219 --> 00:00:53.762
...where Richard Phillips...

5
00:00:53.971 --> 00:00:59.309
...a Merchant Marine captain
working for Maersk Line...

6
00:00:59.518 --> 00:01:02.563
...gets ready to go on a trip...

7
00:01:02.771 --> 00:01:07.150
...something he's done
many. many times before.

8
00:01:10.195 --> 00:01:12.698
There are lots of reasons
why you make a film.

9
00:01:12.906 --> 00:01:18.161
With this one. it was the compelling
story. for me. of two captains.

10
00:01:18.370 --> 00:01:21.248
One from Vermont...

11
00:01:21.456 --> 00:01:24.918
...in charge of a large modern
container ship...

12
00:01:25.127 --> 00:01:28.422
...and the other. a young Somali...

13
00:01:28.630 --> 00:01:31.216
...in charge of a pirate skiff.
And their collision...

14
00:01:31.425 --> 00:01:35.887
...their trial of strength.
their test of wills was really the film.

15
00:01:36.221 --> 00:01:37.472
But also. another reason...

16
00:01:37.681 --> 00:01:40.934
...was that my father was
in the Merchant Marine. at sea all his life.

17
00:01:41.143 --> 00:01:45.647
So I felt I knew about these men
and what their life was.

18
00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:48.859
You all right?

19
00:01:50.193 --> 00:01:53.780
The first scene
is a very important scene. I think...

20
00:01:55.157 --> 00:01:57.618
...between Richard Phillips and his wife...

21
00:01:58.327 --> 00:02:02.789
...in which they really lay out
the thematic ground of the film...

22
00:02:02.998 --> 00:02:04.333
...which is unease.

23
00:02:06.251 --> 00:02:07.502
When we started the film...

24
00:02:07.711 --> 00:02:10.255
...we talked a lot about
the dominant question being:

25
00:02:10.756 --> 00:02:12.507
Are we going to be okay?

26
00:02:14.051 --> 00:02:16.470
I think all of us.
no matter what our professions...

27
00:02:16.678 --> 00:02:19.806
...no matter what our circumstances.
have that sense of unease...

28
00:02:20.015 --> 00:02:26.396
...that the future is not necessarily
going to go as well as the past.

29
00:02:26.605 --> 00:02:29.983
And I wanted that sense...

30
00:02:30.192 --> 00:02:33.987
...of a fast-moving. fast-changing world.

31
00:02:34.196 --> 00:02:36.907
The globalising economy
that drives all of our lives...

32
00:02:37.115 --> 00:02:39.493
...and drives all of our choices.
wherever we are...

33
00:02:42.037 --> 00:02:45.290
...to really underpin the film.

34
00:02:47.334 --> 00:02:50.003
In fact. when we first started the film...

35
00:02:51.463 --> 00:02:55.133
The-- It was based
on Richard Phillips' book...

36
00:02:56.051 --> 00:02:59.513
...which was really the account
of his first-person experiences...

37
00:02:59.721 --> 00:03:02.015
...and his wife's experiences
back in Vermont.

38
00:03:02.432 --> 00:03:04.142
And that was
one of the reasons why...

39
00:03:04.309 --> 00:03:07.938
...we cast that wonderful actress.
Catherine Keener.

40
00:03:08.689 --> 00:03:11.483
As the story-- Or as the development
process unfolded...

41
00:03:11.692 --> 00:03:15.028
...it became clear to me
that our story really lay on the water.

42
00:03:15.237 --> 00:03:18.865
And so we ended up
just with this one scene...

43
00:03:19.032 --> 00:03:21.660
...and I'm forever
in Catherine's debt. She--

44
00:03:21.868 --> 00:03:24.913
I said. "Do you really wanna do this?
It's a very small part now."

45
00:03:25.122 --> 00:03:29.292
And she said. "No. no. I really do."
And she believed in the film.

46
00:03:29.876 --> 00:03:33.964
And she graced us with her presence.

47
00:03:34.172 --> 00:03:36.591
And as I say. I'm forever in her debt.

48
00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:38.135
She's a wonderful actress.

49
00:03:42.848 --> 00:03:46.518
I just wanted these scenes
to be everyday.

50
00:03:46.727 --> 00:03:49.646
Nothing loaded in the farewell.

51
00:03:49.855 --> 00:03:50.856
Just ordinary.

52
00:03:51.022 --> 00:03:53.108
- Have a safe trip.
- I'll call you from there.

53
00:03:53.275 --> 00:03:56.069
A big danger in these sorts of stories
is to play the end...

54
00:03:56.278 --> 00:03:58.780
...to play every scene
with the knowledge of the end...

55
00:03:58.989 --> 00:04:00.657
...so it becomes kind of doom-laden.

56
00:04:00.866 --> 00:04:03.076
But. of course.
there would have been nothing...

57
00:04:03.285 --> 00:04:06.872
...in Richard Phillips' mind
or his wife's mind...

58
00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:10.292
...to suggest that this was anything
other than a routine trip.

59
00:04:12.669 --> 00:04:17.215
And then we cut
to a very different part of the world.

60
00:04:18.133 --> 00:04:19.426
Eyl. Somalia.

61
00:04:22.304 --> 00:04:23.555
A pirate community...

62
00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:27.434
...financed by--

63
00:04:27.642 --> 00:04:29.227
From far away.

64
00:04:29.436 --> 00:04:31.813
- -By organised criminals.

65
00:04:32.230 --> 00:04:34.483
Because the truth
about modern day piracy...

66
00:04:34.691 --> 00:04:39.112
...is it's organised crime
on the high seas.

67
00:04:39.404 --> 00:04:40.822
Hurry. Muse!

68
00:04:42.157 --> 00:04:44.701
And. of course. like organised crime
through history...

69
00:04:44.910 --> 00:04:49.831
...its roots lie in poverty and desperation
and lack of choices.

70
00:04:50.832 --> 00:04:54.586
And we meet a young man. Muse...

71
00:04:55.462 --> 00:04:58.215
...who's a skiff captain.

72
00:05:00.425 --> 00:05:03.845
And I wanted to portray
in these scenes...

73
00:05:05.263 --> 00:05:09.434
...the context
in which criminal choices are made.

74
00:05:11.269 --> 00:05:14.773
And that context. of course.
is the desperate. lawless...

75
00:05:16.149 --> 00:05:19.110
...warlord-dominated.
gangster-dominated...

76
00:05:20.695 --> 00:05:23.073
...impoverished world of Somalia.

77
00:05:25.534 --> 00:05:30.747
And also to set up the rivalry
between Muse...

78
00:05:30.956 --> 00:05:34.584
...and the other pirate-skiff captain.
Asad.

79
00:05:36.378 --> 00:05:38.880
Stay out of my way today.

80
00:05:41.716 --> 00:05:43.969
And to say a little bit...

81
00:05:44.177 --> 00:05:49.808
...about the brutal world...

82
00:05:50.016 --> 00:05:51.351
...of modern piracy.

83
00:05:51.560 --> 00:05:54.437
Muse. take me with you.

84
00:05:54.604 --> 00:05:56.857
These scenes were all shot in Morocco...

85
00:05:57.274 --> 00:06:02.863
...but it was uncannily close
to the coast of Somalia.

86
00:06:04.155 --> 00:06:06.241
And we meet the other pirates.

87
00:06:08.869 --> 00:06:12.038
The young--
The youngest of the four. Bilal...

88
00:06:12.247 --> 00:06:14.124
...carrying the khat...

89
00:06:14.332 --> 00:06:19.546
...which is chewed ubiquitously
by people in Somalia.

90
00:06:20.547 --> 00:06:23.550
It's also considered an antidote
for seasickness...

91
00:06:23.758 --> 00:06:27.053
...which is why a lot
of these young pirates use it.

92
00:06:28.179 --> 00:06:29.431
It's a sort of--

93
00:06:29.639 --> 00:06:32.350
It's the drug of choice in Somalia.

94
00:06:35.562 --> 00:06:38.690
Next time bring me something
if you want to work.

95
00:06:43.028 --> 00:06:46.698
I wanted this scene to carry echoes...

96
00:06:46.907 --> 00:06:50.702
...of that famous scene.
start of <i>On the Waterfront...</i>

97
00:06:52.537 --> 00:06:59.210
...where you see that ruthless people
choose who's to work and who's not.

98
00:07:00.837 --> 00:07:04.925
And that creates
a whole system of control.

99
00:07:07.093 --> 00:07:11.014
But. of course.
you know from this first scene...

100
00:07:13.308 --> 00:07:18.980
...that Muse is going to come into conflict
and collision with Phillips.

101
00:07:20.607 --> 00:07:23.944
The two men whose journeys
are going to meet.

102
00:07:25.403 --> 00:07:27.280
I want him.

103
00:07:28.156 --> 00:07:29.282
That's Najee.

104
00:07:33.161 --> 00:07:35.038
Why did he pick him?

105
00:07:36.039 --> 00:07:38.625
The hard man of the four.
I suppose you'd call him.

106
00:07:41.962 --> 00:07:43.964
So now we know the four of them.

107
00:07:46.758 --> 00:07:48.635
Muse in command. Bilal...

108
00:07:48.843 --> 00:07:50.553
...Najee and Elmi the driver...

109
00:07:51.012 --> 00:07:53.932
...there with the blue fuel bucket...

110
00:07:54.516 --> 00:07:56.309
...and. of course. the ladder.

111
00:08:05.902 --> 00:08:07.904
This was a very difficult scene
to shoot...

112
00:08:08.113 --> 00:08:09.948
...because the swell was very big.

113
00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:12.867
And those boats are quite dangerous.

114
00:08:14.619 --> 00:08:17.706
You know. when they pitch
into the waves...

115
00:08:18.164 --> 00:08:22.419
...there were a lot of safety issues
actually. funnily enough. with that.

116
00:08:22.669 --> 00:08:26.673
As many the-- As with many
of the other scenes on the water...

117
00:08:26.881 --> 00:08:28.883
...safety is always paramount.

118
00:08:29.092 --> 00:08:32.053
Faster. move faster!

119
00:08:32.887 --> 00:08:37.142
And I wanted to show
the relationship...

120
00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:41.438
...between the pressure...

121
00:08:41.646 --> 00:08:45.316
...that a Maersk captain feels under...

122
00:08:47.027 --> 00:08:50.155
...and the way that same pressure
is translated...

123
00:08:50.739 --> 00:08:55.910
...into a vessel off the coast of Somalia.
A pirate vessel off the coast of Somalia.

124
00:08:56.703 --> 00:08:58.955
It's the pressure
of a fast-globalising world...

125
00:08:59.164 --> 00:09:00.582
...but. of course...

126
00:09:01.374 --> 00:09:06.796
...it's a harsher. a more brutal world
down at the bottom.

127
00:09:15.805 --> 00:09:19.017
And I very much
liked Henry Jackman's score there...

128
00:09:19.225 --> 00:09:23.146
...which was a cello...

129
00:09:23.646 --> 00:09:27.192
...with a variety of pans...

130
00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:30.236
...and metal objects...

131
00:09:30.403 --> 00:09:36.117
...used to create percussive sounds
of tension.

132
00:09:39.079 --> 00:09:42.040
So now we come back to Richard
Phillips at Salalah Port. Oman...

133
00:09:42.248 --> 00:09:45.585
...where he joins the <i>Maersk Alabama.</i>

134
00:09:46.294 --> 00:09:48.129
This scene was actually shot...

135
00:09:48.338 --> 00:09:51.007
...on a harbour in Malta.

136
00:09:51.216 --> 00:09:53.802
And we used some small visual effects.
set extensions...

137
00:09:55.178 --> 00:09:59.474
...just to create
the additional sense of scale.

138
00:09:59.766 --> 00:10:01.101
Sign right there. sir.

139
00:10:01.851 --> 00:10:04.270
But it worked really well. I think.

140
00:10:04.646 --> 00:10:07.607
I totally believed
we were in Salalah Port.

141
00:10:10.401 --> 00:10:13.488
One of the big decisions we made
early in this film...

142
00:10:13.696 --> 00:10:17.200
...was to shoot as much
as we possibly could on the water...

143
00:10:17.408 --> 00:10:18.535
...on the ocean...

144
00:10:18.743 --> 00:10:20.537
...and as much as we possibly could...

145
00:10:20.745 --> 00:10:24.040
...on the actual vessels.

146
00:10:24.249 --> 00:10:26.501
This vessel was actually
the <i>Maersk Alexandra...</i>

147
00:10:26.709 --> 00:10:28.169
...an identical sister ship...

148
00:10:28.378 --> 00:10:31.589
...the only sister ship
of the <i>Maersk Alabama.</i>

149
00:10:31.798 --> 00:10:33.258
So it was an identical ship...

150
00:10:33.466 --> 00:10:38.179
...and we were able to hire it
and bring it to Malta.

151
00:10:38.930 --> 00:10:42.142
And it just brought to life...

152
00:10:43.810 --> 00:10:47.147
...the piece in a way that shooting on set
would never have been able to.

153
00:10:47.313 --> 00:10:50.567
Just the detail
of the pirate cages unlocked...

154
00:10:50.775 --> 00:10:53.820
...the engine-room doors unlocked...

155
00:10:54.779 --> 00:10:56.906
...the corridors. the compression...

156
00:10:57.115 --> 00:11:00.076
...the claustrophobia of it all.

157
00:11:00.410 --> 00:11:04.122
It became an adventure for all of us
who made the film too.

158
00:11:04.330 --> 00:11:07.458
Phillips comes
into his captain's quarters...

159
00:11:07.667 --> 00:11:09.961
...and then he starts
by coming up to the bridge.

160
00:11:10.587 --> 00:11:13.715
- Hey. good to see you. Cap.
- Shane. Good to see you.

161
00:11:13.882 --> 00:11:16.384
- Good to see you.
- Hey. Carry on.

162
00:11:16.551 --> 00:11:17.844
- Hey. bos?
- Yeah?

163
00:11:18.803 --> 00:11:21.431
And he meets his chief mate.
Shane Murphy...

164
00:11:22.307 --> 00:11:23.725
...played by Michael Chernus.

165
00:11:23.892 --> 00:11:26.060
- -Grab Jimmy. get on the Lodestar.

166
00:11:27.395 --> 00:11:29.480
It's a tremendous challenge. I think...

167
00:11:29.689 --> 00:11:31.357
...for an actor...

168
00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:34.235
...talking about Tom Hanks here...

169
00:11:34.444 --> 00:11:37.947
...to come in
and be a believable captain...

170
00:11:38.156 --> 00:11:39.532
...of a modern container ship.

171
00:11:39.741 --> 00:11:42.952
There's a huge skill set
that you have to have...

172
00:11:43.161 --> 00:11:46.206
...to be in charge of a ship.

173
00:11:47.415 --> 00:11:50.877
And Tom spent a lot of time
on the <i>Alexandra.</i>

174
00:11:51.085 --> 00:11:55.548
In fact. he took a passage himself
on the ship alone with the crew...

175
00:11:55.757 --> 00:12:01.971
...so that he could see how the ship
was captained by Captain Larsen.

176
00:12:03.598 --> 00:12:05.892
And by the time we started shooting...

177
00:12:06.100 --> 00:12:08.311
...it was amazing to all of us. I think...

178
00:12:08.519 --> 00:12:11.648
...how absolutely believably he slipped...

179
00:12:11.856 --> 00:12:15.610
...into the role of the captain.

180
00:12:15.818 --> 00:12:17.904
- -All the way down to Mombasa.

181
00:12:18.071 --> 00:12:20.156
<i>We need five minutes
on that reefer bow.</i>

182
00:12:23.326 --> 00:12:25.870
We should be able
to unload the containers around 0800.

183
00:12:25.995 --> 00:12:28.706
Always a difficult judgement
to make in a film like this...

184
00:12:28.915 --> 00:12:31.125
...how hard to hit...

185
00:12:32.585 --> 00:12:36.339
...the idea of the dangerous waters.

186
00:12:36.547 --> 00:12:38.383
You have to do it because it's...

187
00:12:39.425 --> 00:12:41.803
Your audience knows
that's where the piece is going.

188
00:12:42.011 --> 00:12:44.389
But you don't want it
to be too heavy-handed...

189
00:12:44.597 --> 00:12:50.311
...and again. I thought
that Henry's score was perfectly judged...

190
00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:54.357
...because you move
from just a little sense of unease...

191
00:12:54.691 --> 00:13:00.113
...into this brass chord...

192
00:13:00.780 --> 00:13:03.283
...that becomes the basis for the score
as we develop.

193
00:13:06.577 --> 00:13:07.662
Tighten it up.

194
00:13:07.829 --> 00:13:09.831
Hey. slow down.

195
00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:16.296
So then we move
into the departure of the <i>Alabama.</i>

196
00:13:17.046 --> 00:13:18.715
We had to use visual effects...

197
00:13:18.923 --> 00:13:22.468
...to change the <i>Alexandra</i>
to the <i>Alabama</i> in that previous shot.

198
00:13:22.677 --> 00:13:25.138
There was little visual-effects work
in the film...

199
00:13:25.346 --> 00:13:29.267
...but most of it was in that shot...

200
00:13:29.475 --> 00:13:32.979
...again. changing the <i>Alabama</i>--
The <i>Alexandra</i> to the <i>Alabama.</i>

201
00:13:33.187 --> 00:13:34.230
Dead slow ahead.

202
00:13:41.362 --> 00:13:45.575
Again. this scene's important
because you need to sell...

203
00:13:45.783 --> 00:13:50.330
...the technological power
of the modern container ship...

204
00:13:50.538 --> 00:13:51.873
...with its huge engines...

205
00:13:52.081 --> 00:13:58.963
...its very full cargo of containers...

206
00:14:00.089 --> 00:14:04.927
...and the high-tech equipment
that Phillips has at his disposal.

207
00:14:07.055 --> 00:14:11.184
And also to sell its fragility.
I always think as you see these shots...

208
00:14:11.392 --> 00:14:14.979
...you feel it's a sort of delicate machine
as well...

209
00:14:15.188 --> 00:14:17.982
...as it cuts its way through the ocean...

210
00:14:18.191 --> 00:14:23.071
...and out towards the Somali Basin.

211
00:14:27.909 --> 00:14:29.827
We talked a lot. Tom and I...

212
00:14:30.036 --> 00:14:33.456
...about trying to get
as authentically as we could...

213
00:14:33.664 --> 00:14:39.212
...to capture the ordinary procedures
of a captain's life.

214
00:14:40.213 --> 00:14:44.801
The three times daily. four times daily.
walking around the deck...

215
00:14:45.009 --> 00:14:47.261
...just to check who's doing what...

216
00:14:47.470 --> 00:14:49.555
...how the cargo is...

217
00:14:49.764 --> 00:14:51.599
...how the ship is.

218
00:14:51.808 --> 00:14:57.063
And in a film like this. the temptation
often is to cut these pieces.

219
00:14:57.271 --> 00:15:00.024
But actually. very often...

220
00:15:00.233 --> 00:15:04.195
...if you take time to set up the world.
to explore the world...

221
00:15:04.612 --> 00:15:05.947
...it pays dividends later...

222
00:15:06.155 --> 00:15:09.534
...because you've become invested.
as an audience. in it...

223
00:15:09.742 --> 00:15:13.746
...as a believable world
with believable characters.

224
00:15:15.289 --> 00:15:20.878
Again. we had to pick the world
of a modern Merchant Marine crew.

225
00:15:21.087 --> 00:15:22.213
It's a hard life.

226
00:15:23.464 --> 00:15:25.675
As I know from my father.
it's a hard life...

227
00:15:25.883 --> 00:15:30.012
...and people who go to sea go to sea
because it's a choice. It's a calling.

228
00:15:39.647 --> 00:15:42.775
And now I think we know
the rhythm of the film.

229
00:15:42.984 --> 00:15:45.194
We're gonna cut
between these two worlds.

230
00:15:47.321 --> 00:15:49.574
Captain Phillips...

231
00:15:49.866 --> 00:15:52.952
...and the young pirate. Captain Muse.

232
00:15:53.661 --> 00:15:56.247
And this is obviously the moment...

233
00:15:57.457 --> 00:16:00.001
...where he sees the <i>Alabama.</i>

234
00:16:00.209 --> 00:16:04.464
He doesn't. of course. know it's that ship
then. but he just knows it as a blip...

235
00:16:04.672 --> 00:16:06.674
...on its own in the ocean.

236
00:16:07.550 --> 00:16:09.969
We know now the collision
we've been waiting for...

237
00:16:10.178 --> 00:16:14.140
...almost from the first moment
of the film. is not far away.

238
00:16:27.111 --> 00:16:29.864
Again. this is another scene that...

239
00:16:30.072 --> 00:16:32.158
You don't want to hurry your audience.

240
00:16:32.366 --> 00:16:37.163
They know where you're going. In many
ways. you want to lean against it.

241
00:16:37.371 --> 00:16:40.500
Phillips receives the warnings.

242
00:16:40.708 --> 00:16:44.170
There were a lot of warnings issued
at that time.

243
00:16:46.047 --> 00:16:49.300
A problem that a Merchant Marine
captain like Phillips had...

244
00:16:49.509 --> 00:16:52.345
...was that they were under instructions
from the company...

245
00:16:52.887 --> 00:16:57.391
...to continue on their route...

246
00:16:57.600 --> 00:17:01.354
...and the warnings were unspecific.

247
00:17:01.562 --> 00:17:05.316
Pirates were attacking hundreds. if not
thousands of miles out into the ocean.

248
00:17:05.525 --> 00:17:07.610
There was no safe distance.

249
00:17:08.736 --> 00:17:12.114
The only way you could get through
was to move as quickly as you could...

250
00:17:12.323 --> 00:17:14.617
...through dangerous waters
and hope for the best.

251
00:17:15.409 --> 00:17:16.786
Ken. you're the duty officer?

252
00:17:16.953 --> 00:17:18.412
- Yeah. Cap.
- Right.

253
00:17:18.579 --> 00:17:21.457
Boat with two armed men is approaching
on your starboard beam.

254
00:17:21.624 --> 00:17:24.919
Phillips was a very diligent...

255
00:17:26.170 --> 00:17:28.631
...and professional captain.

256
00:17:28.839 --> 00:17:34.178
And in the end.
he came to face an enormous challenge.

257
00:17:35.304 --> 00:17:40.351
An unimaginable challenge that--
No U.S. flag carrier...

258
00:17:40.560 --> 00:17:44.605
...had been attacked by pirates
for 200 years.

259
00:17:45.106 --> 00:17:49.902
But through it all. by the end
of this entire sequence of events...

260
00:17:50.111 --> 00:17:51.487
...thanks to his courage...

261
00:17:52.905 --> 00:17:55.575
...his ship was safe.
got to Mombasa safely--

262
00:17:55.783 --> 00:18:00.288
The crew got to Mombasa
safely. unhurt...

263
00:18:00.496 --> 00:18:02.873
...and so did his cargo.

264
00:18:03.499 --> 00:18:06.252
And in that sense.
he fulfilled the three prime duties...

265
00:18:06.460 --> 00:18:08.421
...of a Merchant Marine captain...

266
00:18:08.629 --> 00:18:11.382
...but he did it at risk of his own life.

267
00:18:11.591 --> 00:18:14.343
- Watch it. man.
- Ready with number six.

268
00:18:14.510 --> 00:18:15.636
All right.

269
00:18:16.304 --> 00:18:17.388
You tied up?

270
00:18:17.597 --> 00:18:20.933
So here we are
in the middle of a security drill.

271
00:18:22.059 --> 00:18:24.020
Crew affixed the hoses...

272
00:18:24.228 --> 00:18:26.897
...which are really in the absence
of any armed guards...

273
00:18:27.106 --> 00:18:30.359
...because. of course. in those days.
armed guards weren't carried...

274
00:18:30.568 --> 00:18:34.322
...on Merchant Marine ships
principally for three reasons.

275
00:18:34.530 --> 00:18:38.951
Firstly. you couldn't carry weapons
into many international ports...

276
00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:41.162
...and secondly...

277
00:18:42.913 --> 00:18:45.249
...shipping companies weren't prepared
to pay...

278
00:18:45.458 --> 00:18:49.462
...the additional costs of security details
on ships...

279
00:18:49.670 --> 00:18:51.631
...as they do now since these events.

280
00:18:51.839 --> 00:18:54.550
And thirdly.
captains weren't very keen...

281
00:18:55.343 --> 00:18:59.096
...on having weapons onboard.
you know.

282
00:18:59.305 --> 00:19:02.183
A Saturday-night dispute onboard
being settled with firearms...

283
00:19:02.391 --> 00:19:04.518
...wouldn't have been their choice.

284
00:19:05.770 --> 00:19:08.189
But it left. of course. these ships...

285
00:19:08.397 --> 00:19:11.400
...perilously vulnerable
on the high seas...

286
00:19:12.234 --> 00:19:15.863
...as Phillips discovers now.

287
00:19:16.072 --> 00:19:18.741
What's up. Cap? Everything okay?

288
00:19:18.908 --> 00:19:21.118
I don't like the look of that.

289
00:19:25.706 --> 00:19:29.418
This was the first attack.
we used to call it.

290
00:19:30.127 --> 00:19:31.587
The first of two attacks.

291
00:19:31.796 --> 00:19:33.547
A long sequence.

292
00:19:33.756 --> 00:19:37.051
And the key in sequences like these
is to sort of...

293
00:19:37.259 --> 00:19:43.474
Is to be very clear up front
what the pieces are that you want.

294
00:19:43.683 --> 00:19:46.018
And you've gotta hone
and work at it on the page...

295
00:19:46.644 --> 00:19:49.021
...to be sure
that every single beat is right.

296
00:19:50.272 --> 00:19:53.109
And then when you shoot it.
you've got to try and shoot it...

297
00:19:53.317 --> 00:19:56.696
...as freely as you can
so you get it to live...

298
00:19:56.904 --> 00:20:01.409
...and rather than just be a sequence
of beats or points.

299
00:20:02.034 --> 00:20:03.994
And then...

300
00:20:04.537 --> 00:20:08.791
...when that material is shot.
it goes into the cutting room...

301
00:20:08.999 --> 00:20:13.504
...and I'm lucky enough
to have one of the world's great editors...

302
00:20:13.671 --> 00:20:14.797
...Christopher Rouse...

303
00:20:17.633 --> 00:20:20.594
...collaborating with me on these films.

304
00:20:21.011 --> 00:20:22.680
And the way he puts this together...

305
00:20:22.888 --> 00:20:24.765
...the sense of architecture...

306
00:20:24.974 --> 00:20:28.894
...and the sense of controlled pace...

307
00:20:29.103 --> 00:20:32.398
...the precision of each shot...

308
00:20:33.983 --> 00:20:37.486
...is a master class in editing. I think.
and storytelling.

309
00:20:42.116 --> 00:20:44.160
Now get me U.S. Maritime Emergency.

310
00:20:44.326 --> 00:20:46.746
And a lot of the things
that are being set up here...

311
00:20:46.954 --> 00:20:50.374
...of course. are common
to the second attack.

312
00:20:50.583 --> 00:20:53.669
You've got to understand
how the ship works...

313
00:20:53.878 --> 00:20:56.338
...what the control surfaces
and choices are...

314
00:20:56.547 --> 00:20:58.966
...that are available to the captain...

315
00:21:01.385 --> 00:21:03.763
...if you're to make an assessment
as an audience...

316
00:21:03.929 --> 00:21:06.140
...as to the vulnerability
of their situation.

317
00:21:06.348 --> 00:21:08.184
And the more you understand it...

318
00:21:08.392 --> 00:21:12.354
...the more you engage
with the scenario.

319
00:21:13.481 --> 00:21:15.232
And I think...

320
00:21:17.276 --> 00:21:19.487
...you feel...

321
00:21:20.404 --> 00:21:22.990
...in this performance
from Tom Hanks...

322
00:21:24.241 --> 00:21:29.538
...the absolute concentration he has
in dealing with this unfolding crisis...

323
00:21:30.998 --> 00:21:33.000
...in a very. very believable way.

324
00:21:33.834 --> 00:21:35.961
- -With a possible mothers hip following.

325
00:21:36.128 --> 00:21:38.798
- <i>Potential piracy situation.</i>
- Copy. <i>Alabama.</i>

326
00:21:38.964 --> 00:21:41.759
Alert your crew.
get your fire hoses ready...

327
00:21:41.926 --> 00:21:44.053
<i>...and follow lockdown procedures.</i>

328
00:21:45.346 --> 00:21:46.764
Yeah. Is that it?

329
00:21:46.931 --> 00:21:49.308
This is a scene
that if you wrote it as fiction...

330
00:21:49.475 --> 00:21:51.352
...no one would believe you.

331
00:21:51.560 --> 00:21:53.437
The difference is. it actually happened.

332
00:21:53.771 --> 00:21:56.315
The more that he reached out...

333
00:21:56.524 --> 00:21:57.900
...to the emergency numbers...

334
00:21:58.108 --> 00:22:00.653
...the less help he had.

335
00:22:00.861 --> 00:22:03.864
The more you realise something
important in this film. I think...

336
00:22:04.073 --> 00:22:07.827
...which is that unlike the movie world
where with--

337
00:22:08.035 --> 00:22:11.497
We're led to believe so often
that help can be summoned up...

338
00:22:11.705 --> 00:22:13.457
...in a phone call. you know...

339
00:22:14.458 --> 00:22:18.671
...that actually.
if you're a container ship...

340
00:22:18.879 --> 00:22:21.632
...thousands of miles away
in the middle of the ocean...

341
00:22:21.841 --> 00:22:24.552
...there's nothing anybody can do.
You're on your own.

342
00:22:28.055 --> 00:22:32.977
Now we get a sight of Muse
coming towards the vessel.

343
00:22:34.395 --> 00:22:36.939
He and his rival. Asad...

344
00:22:38.649 --> 00:22:41.110
...riding what looked
like modern chariots.

345
00:22:41.443 --> 00:22:43.988
Very. very hard to get those shots.

346
00:22:45.072 --> 00:22:46.699
Hard from a safety point of view--

347
00:22:46.907 --> 00:22:50.744
Very hard for all the actors in the skiffs
to keep their balance...

348
00:22:50.953 --> 00:22:53.372
...in those immense seas.
but very. very hard for us.

349
00:22:53.581 --> 00:22:59.128
We had to use a crane
on a cantilevered arm...

350
00:23:00.087 --> 00:23:04.049
...to keep it steady enough
to get these shots.

351
00:23:04.258 --> 00:23:06.176
They're remarkable
and you really feel...

352
00:23:06.385 --> 00:23:08.679
...the weight of water...

353
00:23:08.888 --> 00:23:11.724
...and the power...

354
00:23:14.101 --> 00:23:17.104
...of the skiff through the--
Through the swell.

355
00:23:24.987 --> 00:23:27.740
Another moment. I remember
reading Richard Phillips' book...

356
00:23:27.948 --> 00:23:33.787
...when he gave the account
of making the fake emergency call.

357
00:23:34.371 --> 00:23:36.332
Again. one of those moments
in the story...

358
00:23:36.540 --> 00:23:40.461
...where I thought. if you made that up.
no one would believe you. It's such a...

359
00:23:41.420 --> 00:23:44.465
An outrageous manoeuvre.

360
00:23:44.673 --> 00:23:46.133
But he did do it.

361
00:23:46.342 --> 00:23:48.093
And as you see. it almost worked.

362
00:23:48.260 --> 00:23:51.347
<i>Our speed is 18.5 knots.</i>

363
00:23:51.555 --> 00:23:54.308
<i>We are being approached
by two pirate skiffs--</i>

364
00:23:54.475 --> 00:23:55.517
The good thing is...

365
00:23:57.019 --> 00:24:00.439
...you're starting to build connectivity
between the characters...

366
00:24:00.648 --> 00:24:02.566
...between Phillips and Muse...

367
00:24:03.233 --> 00:24:05.319
...between Muse and Asad...

368
00:24:05.527 --> 00:24:07.947
...and between Muse and Asad
and the mothers hip.

369
00:24:08.155 --> 00:24:12.201
So your audience is clear all the time
about who the protagonists are...

370
00:24:12.409 --> 00:24:14.870
...where they are. and what's occurring.

371
00:24:15.829 --> 00:24:19.875
And the truth of any action sequence is:

372
00:24:21.460 --> 00:24:25.089
The clearer you are about the characters
and what they want...

373
00:24:25.297 --> 00:24:28.509
...the clearer you are
about the relationships between them...

374
00:24:28.717 --> 00:24:34.014
...the clearer you are
about the physical spaces they inhabit...

375
00:24:34.223 --> 00:24:40.062
...and the more precision you can give
each move and countermove--

376
00:24:40.521 --> 00:24:43.524
Each detail in the unfolding story.

377
00:24:43.899 --> 00:24:46.527
- -The better your action will be.

378
00:24:46.735 --> 00:24:50.322
It's a great mistake. in my view.
to create generality...

379
00:24:50.531 --> 00:24:51.991
...in an action sequence.

380
00:24:52.199 --> 00:24:53.826
Come on! Keep going!

381
00:24:56.286 --> 00:24:59.456
Cutting very fast
and waving the camera...

382
00:25:00.165 --> 00:25:03.627
...does not give you true engagement
as an audience.

383
00:25:03.836 --> 00:25:06.964
Only precision and detail...

384
00:25:08.257 --> 00:25:12.177
...painstakingly put together
in the right order...

385
00:25:12.386 --> 00:25:17.516
...so that you feel an overall
building architecture in the sequence--

386
00:25:17.725 --> 00:25:20.811
That's what gives you great action.
in my view.

387
00:25:26.358 --> 00:25:27.693
So now we see the...

388
00:25:30.029 --> 00:25:34.658
The great advantage
that the modern container ship has.

389
00:25:35.159 --> 00:25:37.536
And you can say it in one word.
It's power.

390
00:25:39.830 --> 00:25:43.542
Those enormous--
The thrust of those enormous engines...

391
00:25:43.751 --> 00:25:45.169
...powering them forward...

392
00:25:47.546 --> 00:25:49.590
...creating an enormous wake...

393
00:25:49.798 --> 00:25:54.928
...that it's very hard for the skiffs
to get through.

394
00:25:57.181 --> 00:26:03.771
And in the end.
when engine is pitted against engine in--

395
00:26:03.979 --> 00:26:05.522
As it is in this sequence...

396
00:26:05.731 --> 00:26:07.733
...there's really only gonna be
one winner.

397
00:26:20.788 --> 00:26:24.416
Because at this stage
in this sequence now...

398
00:26:24.958 --> 00:26:27.669
...we finally got Phillips and Muse...

399
00:26:27.878 --> 00:26:30.005
...in a relationship with each other...

400
00:26:31.173 --> 00:26:32.549
...where they're locked up...

401
00:26:33.050 --> 00:26:38.847
...and that leads to this moment
through the binoculars coming up...

402
00:26:39.056 --> 00:26:43.811
...which obviously is a profound stage
in their relationship.

403
00:26:44.019 --> 00:26:46.480
It's the point in their relationship...

404
00:26:46.688 --> 00:26:48.816
...where both have seen each other.

405
00:26:54.530 --> 00:26:57.950
And. of course. we know
that they'll meet again.

406
00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:03.622
But for the moment...

407
00:27:04.540 --> 00:27:07.292
...first round to Captain Phillips.

408
00:27:11.630 --> 00:27:15.175
And again.
you get those brass chords...

409
00:27:15.384 --> 00:27:18.262
...which are beautifully judged
by Henry.

410
00:27:18.637 --> 00:27:21.390
Alternately reassuring...

411
00:27:21.807 --> 00:27:24.101
...and disquieting.

412
00:27:25.102 --> 00:27:27.396
Complete paradox.
complete contradiction.

413
00:27:28.147 --> 00:27:29.773
But it's the way that score works.

414
00:27:29.982 --> 00:27:33.360
It offers you both at various times.

415
00:27:33.527 --> 00:27:35.654
- -Both with armed intruders.

416
00:27:35.821 --> 00:27:40.534
Now. we all know that's a hazard
in these waters. but you performed well.

417
00:27:41.952 --> 00:27:44.037
This was an important scene
in the film...

418
00:27:44.746 --> 00:27:48.333
...when Phillips talks to his crew.

419
00:27:50.919 --> 00:27:53.338
And we can feel...

420
00:27:54.882 --> 00:27:58.218
...how each reacts to what's occurred.

421
00:28:00.262 --> 00:28:03.432
How do you deal with the fact
that you've been attacked by pirates...

422
00:28:03.640 --> 00:28:06.935
...when you're thousands of miles
from any safety?

423
00:28:07.102 --> 00:28:08.478
Cap.

424
00:28:10.522 --> 00:28:11.648
They're coming back.

425
00:28:11.815 --> 00:28:14.526
Amen. Yeah. that's right.
They're coming back.

426
00:28:14.693 --> 00:28:18.322
If they come back.
we'll follow procedure.

427
00:28:18.488 --> 00:28:21.742
We know when we see Phillips there
that he knows that too.

428
00:28:23.869 --> 00:28:27.748
We will follow the procedures even if
we have to shut down. lock down...

429
00:28:27.915 --> 00:28:29.750
...go dead in the water
and wait for help.

430
00:28:29.917 --> 00:28:33.337
It's interesting this--
That was the state of mind...

431
00:28:33.545 --> 00:28:36.757
...both of Merchant Marine crews...

432
00:28:36.965 --> 00:28:39.009
...and captains.
and also shipping companies.

433
00:28:39.218 --> 00:28:43.680
They believed that ships
with a free board--

434
00:28:43.889 --> 00:28:46.725
That's to say a distance
from ocean to deck...

435
00:28:46.934 --> 00:28:48.435
...of greater than 15 feet...

436
00:28:48.644 --> 00:28:51.438
...and a speed through the water
of greater than 15 knots...

437
00:28:51.647 --> 00:28:53.398
...both of which <i>Maersk Alabama</i> had.

438
00:28:53.607 --> 00:28:56.860
In other words. it was believed
that the biggest container ships...

439
00:28:57.444 --> 00:29:00.280
...were not able to be attacked
by pirates...

440
00:29:00.489 --> 00:29:05.285
...that they would prefer to go for tankers
that were lower in the water. small--

441
00:29:05.494 --> 00:29:08.455
Particularly smaller ones
that didn't have very much speed.

442
00:29:10.791 --> 00:29:14.503
And here. Phillips articulates
the central difficulty.

443
00:29:14.711 --> 00:29:17.714
There is no safe place to go.
There is no running away.

444
00:29:20.342 --> 00:29:22.719
In the months
before this particular attack...

445
00:29:23.387 --> 00:29:25.889
...pirate attacks were recorded
in the Indian Ocean...

446
00:29:26.056 --> 00:29:29.184
...as far as 1200 miles
from the Somali coast...

447
00:29:29.393 --> 00:29:32.020
...because they had these
motherships...

448
00:29:32.229 --> 00:29:36.566
...that they used to carry the skiffs out
hundreds and thousands of miles...

449
00:29:36.775 --> 00:29:41.363
...out into the ocean
to look for unsuspecting shipping.

450
00:29:53.292 --> 00:29:57.838
I just wanted to remind the audience...

451
00:29:58.463 --> 00:30:01.717
...that Phillips had a life
beyond the ship.

452
00:30:02.134 --> 00:30:04.511
A wife. a family.

453
00:30:04.803 --> 00:30:06.930
And also...

454
00:30:07.139 --> 00:30:08.890
...that he was doing...

455
00:30:09.224 --> 00:30:12.978
...what I think all Merchant Marine
captains would do...

456
00:30:13.186 --> 00:30:18.942
...which is to keep their anxieties
well away from their family.

457
00:30:20.652 --> 00:30:24.614
Hufan. I'm telling you.
our boat couldn't take it.

458
00:30:25.198 --> 00:30:29.786
Now. we cut back to the inquest
on the pirate mothers hip.

459
00:30:31.288 --> 00:30:33.623
And we start to learn something
about Asad.

460
00:30:33.832 --> 00:30:35.250
What we know. of course...

461
00:30:35.459 --> 00:30:39.963
...and Muse knows that Asad bailed
in the attack.

462
00:30:40.380 --> 00:30:43.508
So he's giving his excuses early...

463
00:30:43.967 --> 00:30:49.222
...whereas young Muse is only interested
in trying to get a larger ladder...

464
00:30:49.431 --> 00:30:52.100
...and more power to the engine.

465
00:30:53.393 --> 00:30:56.813
He's seen the big prize...

466
00:30:57.147 --> 00:30:59.191
...and we know he's determined
to get it.

467
00:31:00.359 --> 00:31:02.986
But first. he has to deal with his rival.

468
00:31:05.655 --> 00:31:10.285
Shut up. Skinny. You talk too much.

469
00:31:10.952 --> 00:31:13.747
I may be skinny. but I'm not a coward.

470
00:31:20.420 --> 00:31:22.672
Muse's nickname...

471
00:31:22.881 --> 00:31:25.384
...was Skinny Rat or Skinny.

472
00:31:27.803 --> 00:31:31.473
I loved it as a piece of detail
and so did Barkhad Abdi.

473
00:31:33.350 --> 00:31:34.393
And he used it...

474
00:31:35.936 --> 00:31:38.855
...to build this particular moment
when he's--

475
00:31:39.064 --> 00:31:41.733
Stands up for himself
and becomes formidable.

476
00:31:46.196 --> 00:31:50.409
We know in this moment
that Phillips has a real adversary.

477
00:31:53.954 --> 00:31:56.289
One of the other important decisions
in our film...

478
00:31:56.498 --> 00:32:01.294
...was to cast young Somali actors
to play the parts of the--

479
00:32:01.503 --> 00:32:03.630
Of all the pirates. in fact.

480
00:32:04.256 --> 00:32:06.842
We found those actors...

481
00:32:07.801 --> 00:32:11.680
Well. a lot of the smaller parts
were found in the U.K.

482
00:32:11.888 --> 00:32:15.016
But the four principal pirates
were found in Minneapolis...

483
00:32:15.225 --> 00:32:18.854
...which is the largest
Somali community in the U.S.

484
00:32:19.146 --> 00:32:24.276
Obviously. there's no Somali acting
community in Los Angeles or New York.

485
00:32:24.484 --> 00:32:26.528
And Francine Maisler.
our casting director...

486
00:32:26.736 --> 00:32:32.659
...and her colleagues
really had the job of finding them.

487
00:32:32.868 --> 00:32:34.953
And when they went there...

488
00:32:35.162 --> 00:32:38.957
...they found that that community
was rich and vibrant...

489
00:32:39.166 --> 00:32:44.421
...filled with storytellers and musicians
and writers and actors.

490
00:32:44.629 --> 00:32:48.758
And we were very lucky to have
these four young men play the parts.

491
00:32:48.967 --> 00:32:50.844
- Where are they?
- Port quarter.

492
00:32:51.011 --> 00:32:52.721
One-point-seven miles. captain.

493
00:32:54.097 --> 00:32:56.975
So now we begin the second attack.

494
00:32:57.184 --> 00:32:59.853
And the trick here
is to step the pace up...

495
00:33:00.061 --> 00:33:03.815
...so you feel that
the throttle of the film...

496
00:33:05.609 --> 00:33:08.653
...has just been pressed down
a little more.

497
00:33:11.698 --> 00:33:17.120
And I think it's at this stage in the film
that I always feel...

498
00:33:17.329 --> 00:33:20.123
...that Tom's performance...

499
00:33:21.708 --> 00:33:25.921
...starts to really
completely dominate the film.

500
00:33:26.129 --> 00:33:28.256
I want max revs. Take the limits off.

501
00:33:28.423 --> 00:33:34.721
You feel that somewhere in his eyes
is a kind of existential fear.

502
00:33:34.930 --> 00:33:40.477
It's not really just about
skiffs taking over the ships.

503
00:33:42.562 --> 00:33:47.150
It's some unimaginable crisis
that he's facing.

504
00:33:48.818 --> 00:33:55.075
And. of course.
that sense of crisis drives the film.

505
00:33:55.242 --> 00:33:57.202
U.S. Maritime Emergency line.

506
00:33:58.203 --> 00:34:01.665
This is the <i>Maersk Alabama.</i>
We are under pirate attack at a...

507
00:34:01.831 --> 00:34:04.584
- What's happening?
- Ken. get out here.

508
00:34:04.793 --> 00:34:07.796
- I need eyes on the wing. Skiff coming in.
- I'm on it.

509
00:34:07.963 --> 00:34:12.384
Now. it's become one tiny skiff
versus one large ship.

510
00:34:12.801 --> 00:34:14.844
And we're going
through those same gears...

511
00:34:15.053 --> 00:34:17.639
...that we went through in first attack.
but--

512
00:34:17.847 --> 00:34:21.476
But quicker. with more urgency.

513
00:34:21.685 --> 00:34:24.187
More sense of desperation
under the surface.

514
00:34:26.273 --> 00:34:29.859
Somali coast guard.
This is a routine check.

515
00:34:30.068 --> 00:34:31.903
The score here is very. very clever.

516
00:34:32.112 --> 00:34:37.701
It's mixing pulse and tempo.
which is perfectly judged. incidentally...

517
00:34:37.909 --> 00:34:41.329
...and the sort of plangent brass...

518
00:34:42.622 --> 00:34:48.044
...lines that. as I say.
are both comforting...

519
00:34:48.253 --> 00:34:51.381
...and disquieting all at the same time.

520
00:34:51.756 --> 00:34:53.842
Are they consolation
or are they warning?

521
00:34:55.844 --> 00:34:59.180
Very. very skilful scoring here
by Henry Jackman.

522
00:35:00.640 --> 00:35:02.017
Stop the ship.

523
00:35:03.768 --> 00:35:06.313
They're not stopping.

524
00:35:07.063 --> 00:35:08.982
Show them who we are. Muse.

525
00:35:12.110 --> 00:35:13.903
Shoot at them!

526
00:35:17.699 --> 00:35:20.535
Shots fired! Shots fired! Hit the hoses.

527
00:35:20.702 --> 00:35:23.955
Fateful moment in our story
when the shots are first fired.

528
00:35:24.998 --> 00:35:28.001
Obviously. the pace kicks up again.

529
00:35:28.460 --> 00:35:30.253
Turn!

530
00:35:31.504 --> 00:35:35.759
Now we see Phillips deploy.
really. the--

531
00:35:36.259 --> 00:35:38.219
The last line of defence.

532
00:35:38.428 --> 00:35:44.768
The sea hoses that can be used
to stop a small skiff getting alongside.

533
00:35:51.858 --> 00:35:55.362
I love the visual--
The visuals of this film.

534
00:35:55.570 --> 00:35:58.948
From first moment really.
when thinking about it...

535
00:35:59.157 --> 00:36:04.287
...I loved the idea of the perfect
symmetry of the first half of the film...

536
00:36:05.038 --> 00:36:10.710
...being about a large container ship
being chased by a very small skiff...

537
00:36:10.919 --> 00:36:14.881
...and the large container ship
throwing out these hoses...

538
00:36:15.090 --> 00:36:19.636
...and the relationship between the craft
and the water and the cargo.

539
00:36:19.844 --> 00:36:23.473
This all felt very visually interesting.
Then the second half of the film...

540
00:36:23.682 --> 00:36:25.433
...being a complete mirror opposite.

541
00:36:25.642 --> 00:36:29.813
A tiny lifeboat chased
by these enormous warships.

542
00:36:35.652 --> 00:36:38.321
This was a very complicated sequence
to plan and shoot.

543
00:36:38.530 --> 00:36:43.159
There were a lot of safety issues
involved with bringing skiffs...

544
00:36:44.244 --> 00:36:46.663
...up-close
to a speeding container ship.

545
00:36:46.871 --> 00:36:50.917
Obviously. the undertow from one
of those container ships is lethal.

546
00:36:52.919 --> 00:36:55.547
There were a lot of issues
with safe distances...

547
00:36:55.755 --> 00:36:59.050
...and trying to make sure
we could do what we needed to.

548
00:37:01.845 --> 00:37:05.682
Marrying up all these different pieces
and the geography of the skiffs...

549
00:37:05.890 --> 00:37:09.394
...and the firing of the-- Of the flare...

550
00:37:11.396 --> 00:37:13.356
...all involved an awful lot of planning.

551
00:37:17.777 --> 00:37:20.989
But these four young actors
were very. very game.

552
00:37:21.197 --> 00:37:23.199
It was no joke to be out
in those skiffs...

553
00:37:23.408 --> 00:37:26.745
...in the middle of swell
and not wearing much. incidentally...

554
00:37:28.705 --> 00:37:32.500
...for hour after hour after hour.
day after day after day.

555
00:37:32.709 --> 00:37:35.336
It was a considerable feat
of physical endurance...

556
00:37:35.545 --> 00:37:38.798
...and also of seamanship too.
They had several months of training...

557
00:37:39.007 --> 00:37:42.844
...to be able to. you know.
drive those skiffs effectively.

558
00:37:46.931 --> 00:37:48.266
All crew! All crew!

559
00:37:48.433 --> 00:37:51.227
All crew to the engine room!
All crew to the engine room now!

560
00:37:51.394 --> 00:37:53.563
Well. actually.
they were incredibly game. It--

561
00:37:53.772 --> 00:37:56.900
Most of our time was spent
trying to stop them...

562
00:37:57.859 --> 00:38:00.111
...doing things
that wouldn't have been safe.

563
00:38:01.821 --> 00:38:07.702
They were fantastically determined
and fantastically hardworking.

564
00:38:09.329 --> 00:38:11.873
- Port. 30 degrees.
- Port. 30 degrees.

565
00:38:15.293 --> 00:38:19.964
So now we're at the end
of the second attack.

566
00:38:20.590 --> 00:38:23.927
I think Phillips knows it's--
Time is running out.

567
00:38:25.637 --> 00:38:28.306
He tries to turn--
Twist and turn the ship...

568
00:38:28.515 --> 00:38:33.144
...to create an impact
that can throw them off.

569
00:38:33.686 --> 00:38:36.356
But. of course.
the guys who drive these skiffs...

570
00:38:36.564 --> 00:38:39.192
...are very. very skilful...

571
00:38:39.400 --> 00:38:44.989
...at navigating the undertow
and the swell and the hoses...

572
00:38:45.198 --> 00:38:50.286
...and keeping the skiff there
just long enough to get onboard.

573
00:38:53.832 --> 00:38:55.625
But even so. it's a--

574
00:38:55.834 --> 00:38:58.962
It's a very. very dangerous game.

575
00:38:59.170 --> 00:39:02.757
One slip and you're under that ship
and dead.

576
00:39:08.263 --> 00:39:10.890
- Starboard. 30 degrees.
- Starboard. 30.

577
00:39:15.353 --> 00:39:17.814
I love the way Tom sells...

578
00:39:20.108 --> 00:39:23.444
...the sense of dread.
the sense of confusion.

579
00:39:24.529 --> 00:39:28.074
Because he suddenly realises
that his ship has been taken.

580
00:39:28.783 --> 00:39:30.577
- Cronan. Cronan.
- Yeah.

581
00:39:31.911 --> 00:39:35.874
The crew are taken down
to the engine control room.

582
00:39:36.541 --> 00:39:40.628
Head count. and they're gonna try
and hide them down in the engine room.

583
00:39:41.045 --> 00:39:43.172
Meanwhile.
the chief engineer. Mike Perry...

584
00:39:45.049 --> 00:39:49.178
...acting with fantastic professionalism
and dedication...

585
00:39:49.929 --> 00:39:55.310
...is ensuring that the ship's engines
are turned off. disabling the ship.

586
00:39:57.854 --> 00:40:00.440
The roles played by the crew--

587
00:40:00.648 --> 00:40:05.153
One of the things I wanted to do
in this film was to pay proper regard...

588
00:40:05.361 --> 00:40:08.781
...to the way that the crew.
independently of Phillips...

589
00:40:08.990 --> 00:40:15.496
...worked towards the successful
resolution of this host a-- Crisis.

590
00:40:16.247 --> 00:40:17.957
They weren't just passive bystanders.

591
00:40:18.166 --> 00:40:21.544
They worked together
and exhibited great courage...

592
00:40:21.753 --> 00:40:25.131
...and particularly. I think.
Shane Murphy and Mike Perry.

593
00:40:26.341 --> 00:40:28.343
But they all did. They all did.

594
00:40:32.013 --> 00:40:33.848
Jesus.

595
00:40:34.057 --> 00:40:37.310
If the pirates find you. remember.
you know the ship.

596
00:40:38.019 --> 00:40:40.688
So now we're waiting
for the confrontation.

597
00:40:41.940 --> 00:40:44.359
We'd been shooting quite a while
when we shot this...

598
00:40:44.567 --> 00:40:48.196
...but it was always my intention to
keep Tom away from the four pirates...

599
00:40:48.404 --> 00:40:50.490
...away from Barkhad. so that they--

600
00:40:50.698 --> 00:40:52.867
The moment they would first
see each other...

601
00:40:53.076 --> 00:40:55.119
...was the moment they came
through the door.

602
00:40:55.328 --> 00:40:57.413
They knew of each other.
knew they were there.

603
00:40:57.622 --> 00:40:59.666
We kept them in separate parts
of the ship.

604
00:40:59.874 --> 00:41:02.043
We rehearsed this scene separately...

605
00:41:02.251 --> 00:41:08.216
...and then this take
was literally the first time they met.

606
00:41:10.468 --> 00:41:16.140
And it gave it a sense of drama
and a sense of anticipation...

607
00:41:16.349 --> 00:41:18.559
...that it might not otherwise have had.

608
00:41:24.273 --> 00:41:26.985
- Hey! Don't move! Don't move!
- Okay. okay.

609
00:41:27.151 --> 00:41:30.029
- Don't move. I said! Don't move!
- All right. All right.

610
00:41:31.322 --> 00:41:34.117
When you cast
four young unknown actors...

611
00:41:34.325 --> 00:41:35.868
Don't move! We have four!

612
00:41:36.077 --> 00:41:39.205
...starting on their careers
for the first time...

613
00:41:39.831 --> 00:41:42.250
...you never know how it's gonna go...

614
00:41:43.126 --> 00:41:46.212
...until you actually see them
face-to-face.

615
00:41:46.421 --> 00:41:50.758
Here is the moment when a young actor
Barkhad Abdi comes face-to-face...

616
00:41:50.967 --> 00:41:55.388
...with two-time Academy Award-winner
Tom Hanks.

617
00:41:55.722 --> 00:42:01.436
Can he do it?
Has he got the desire and the ability...

618
00:42:01.769 --> 00:42:03.271
...to dominate Tom?

619
00:42:03.479 --> 00:42:05.732
That was the question in my mind.

620
00:42:05.940 --> 00:42:07.608
And I suspect in Tom's too.

621
00:42:08.151 --> 00:42:10.903
When we get paid.
everything gonna be okay.

622
00:42:11.112 --> 00:42:14.657
But you could tell.
as soon as this scene started...

623
00:42:17.201 --> 00:42:18.661
...that he was determined...

624
00:42:20.872 --> 00:42:25.251
...to give Tom
a complete run for his money.

625
00:42:26.669 --> 00:42:29.213
To be his equal on-screen.

626
00:42:32.175 --> 00:42:35.678
To be the thing you most want
in a film.

627
00:42:36.054 --> 00:42:39.766
To be a formidable adversary.

628
00:42:41.142 --> 00:42:45.855
It's a remarkable piece of acting
by a young man from Minneapolis...

629
00:42:46.064 --> 00:42:48.691
...who had never acted before.
professionally.

630
00:42:48.858 --> 00:42:50.860
TV and car--? No. no.
We just got the food--

631
00:42:51.027 --> 00:42:52.737
Dollars?

632
00:42:53.279 --> 00:42:56.908
We do. Kenny?
Kenny. what do we have in the safe?

633
00:42:57.075 --> 00:43:02.163
The way he laces the performance
with humour and self-doubt.

634
00:43:02.622 --> 00:43:07.752
He will let any one moment
to be incredibly menacing...

635
00:43:07.960 --> 00:43:13.007
...but also oddly vulnerable.

636
00:43:19.347 --> 00:43:21.390
What's that?

637
00:43:25.394 --> 00:43:26.437
It's all right.

638
00:43:26.604 --> 00:43:28.940
Hey. calm down! Calm down.

639
00:43:29.107 --> 00:43:31.234
Get back there.

640
00:43:31.400 --> 00:43:34.487
So this sequence really begins the--

641
00:43:34.695 --> 00:43:39.033
The section of the film that deals
with what happened in that first day...

642
00:43:39.242 --> 00:43:40.785
...when the pirates got onboard.

643
00:43:42.370 --> 00:43:43.996
Phillips was up on the--

644
00:43:45.414 --> 00:43:49.627
On the control. on the bridge.
with a couple of crew members...

645
00:43:50.044 --> 00:43:52.922
...and the crew were hiding down below
in the engine room.

646
00:43:54.215 --> 00:43:59.929
And the problem the pirates had was
they needed to get the rest of the crew.

647
00:44:00.138 --> 00:44:05.226
Phillips was determined that the pirates
would not get any more hostages.

648
00:44:07.645 --> 00:44:08.980
Watch this ugly one.

649
00:44:18.573 --> 00:44:20.366
What are you doing?

650
00:44:20.533 --> 00:44:22.743
I'm going to fix it.

651
00:44:23.536 --> 00:44:27.248
I like this part of the scene
because it's asking the question:

652
00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:35.673
How much does a young Somali
pirate captain understand...

653
00:44:36.924 --> 00:44:40.052
...a sophisticated
modern container ship?

654
00:44:41.637 --> 00:44:43.222
The answer is not very much.

655
00:44:44.807 --> 00:44:49.812
But out of that. you start to develop
the relationship between Muse...

656
00:44:50.855 --> 00:44:52.148
Where is the crew?

657
00:44:52.356 --> 00:44:54.859
I don't know. I don't know.
I'm here with you.

658
00:44:55.735 --> 00:44:56.861
...and Najee.

659
00:44:59.405 --> 00:45:02.241
And that relationship. that...

660
00:45:02.867 --> 00:45:08.080
...test of strength between the two
of them that goes on alongside the--

661
00:45:08.289 --> 00:45:11.042
The battle
between Phillips and Muse...

662
00:45:12.585 --> 00:45:16.422
...is what comes to dominate
the second half of the film.

663
00:45:18.257 --> 00:45:21.177
Another minute. I kill somebody.

664
00:45:21.636 --> 00:45:25.223
<i>I kill all your friends. One minute.</i>

665
00:45:25.389 --> 00:45:27.475
<i>I will no call again.</i>

666
00:45:30.311 --> 00:45:33.272
Get that one
and put him against the wall.

667
00:45:33.856 --> 00:45:35.691
- I'm trying--
- You think we playing?

668
00:45:35.858 --> 00:45:38.277
- No. I'm doing the best--
- No play. No play.

669
00:45:39.654 --> 00:45:43.199
These must have been
desperate moments...

670
00:45:43.658 --> 00:45:45.701
...on the bridge and in the engine room.

671
00:45:45.910 --> 00:45:47.578
- Come on.
- You play? You play?

672
00:45:47.745 --> 00:45:48.788
Who was to know...

673
00:45:50.665 --> 00:45:53.960
...whether someone wasn't gonna get
a bullet in the head very soon?

674
00:45:54.710 --> 00:45:57.088
In a sense. there was no right
or wrong thing to do.

675
00:45:57.296 --> 00:46:00.841
To disclose where the crew were
might have made things worse.

676
00:46:01.050 --> 00:46:04.178
Not to disclose the crew
might have made things worse.

677
00:46:04.387 --> 00:46:08.808
It was the terrible choices...

678
00:46:10.559 --> 00:46:12.228
...that people had to make that day.

679
00:46:12.395 --> 00:46:13.646
- You killing him.
- It's my ship.

680
00:46:13.813 --> 00:46:15.815
- Listen to me.
- You killing him.

681
00:46:15.982 --> 00:46:17.775
I'm the captain.

682
00:46:17.942 --> 00:46:19.110
But I think the--

683
00:46:20.569 --> 00:46:22.363
The acting in this scene...

684
00:46:22.571 --> 00:46:28.452
...the company of actors
inhabiting. totally. this situation...

685
00:46:29.704 --> 00:46:30.913
...I think. is exemplary.

686
00:46:31.122 --> 00:46:33.457
Corey Johnson there
with the gun to his head.

687
00:46:34.834 --> 00:46:36.961
He's done a number of films with me.

688
00:46:37.169 --> 00:46:38.796
Always...

689
00:46:39.880 --> 00:46:46.679
...always absolutely beautifully accurate
in everything he does. and human.

690
00:46:53.102 --> 00:46:55.021
I want to search the ship.

691
00:46:56.564 --> 00:46:59.775
One of the things I tried to do
in this film...

692
00:46:59.984 --> 00:47:04.613
...was create a rise and fall. a pitch.
a sort of--

693
00:47:07.533 --> 00:47:10.536
An undulating sense of tension...

694
00:47:10.953 --> 00:47:13.331
<i>We better hope
the emergency power stays on.</i>

695
00:47:14.707 --> 00:47:19.837
...that sort of replicates
the structure of the ocean itself.

696
00:47:21.505 --> 00:47:26.093
And that's driven. of course. ultimately
by the tension...

697
00:47:26.302 --> 00:47:28.637
...between the two characters.
Muse and Phillips...

698
00:47:28.846 --> 00:47:32.975
...but also the tension
within the pirates...

699
00:47:33.184 --> 00:47:37.063
...as the pitch of panic and--

700
00:47:37.271 --> 00:47:39.065
And relaxation ebbs and flows.

701
00:47:41.233 --> 00:47:44.612
And capturing that in the right way...

702
00:47:45.029 --> 00:47:49.867
...so that you can vary the pace
in the film...

703
00:47:50.951 --> 00:47:55.039
...dominated a lot of my thinking
in the run-up to the film.

704
00:47:55.247 --> 00:47:58.918
I'm gonna go to the mess. get water.
Get everyone on the lower level.

705
00:47:59.085 --> 00:48:00.878
All right. I'm on 2.

706
00:48:09.011 --> 00:48:11.847
There's Henry's brass chord again...

707
00:48:12.598 --> 00:48:14.725
...just anchoring you...

708
00:48:18.187 --> 00:48:21.565
...keeping the humanity
of the piece alive.

709
00:48:22.983 --> 00:48:25.152
Early on. we experimented...

710
00:48:25.361 --> 00:48:28.531
...with more electronic versions
of the score. but--

711
00:48:28.739 --> 00:48:33.244
But I think we all agreed that the--

712
00:48:34.370 --> 00:48:36.372
You know...

713
00:48:36.956 --> 00:48:42.128
...the human-scale instruments.
brass and wood...

714
00:48:42.545 --> 00:48:44.463
...and cello...

715
00:48:46.132 --> 00:48:47.967
...were where the score needs to sit...

716
00:48:48.175 --> 00:48:51.345
...and that's ultimately the direction
we went in.

717
00:48:55.808 --> 00:48:58.227
This is a very important scene...

718
00:48:58.436 --> 00:49:02.440
...as the relationship
between Phillips and Muse develops...

719
00:49:03.774 --> 00:49:07.153
...and as you realise
that each is lying to the other...

720
00:49:08.362 --> 00:49:10.698
...and each knows it.

721
00:49:10.906 --> 00:49:14.702
And that's a difficult story
for an actor to tell.

722
00:49:15.119 --> 00:49:18.747
- -We're working our way down.
so we should try the cargo deck.

723
00:49:19.331 --> 00:49:23.878
You don't want to signpost it too much.
but it's got to be there.

724
00:49:24.086 --> 00:49:26.130
And I really think...

725
00:49:26.922 --> 00:49:31.427
...that you start to really engage now
in this scene with the--

726
00:49:31.635 --> 00:49:34.638
With the battle of wits
between each character.

727
00:49:34.805 --> 00:49:37.558
Maybe we should get some water
from the mess down on A deck?

728
00:49:42.313 --> 00:49:45.566
- Then engine room. Go.
- Okay.

729
00:49:45.733 --> 00:49:49.653
He knows that he's lying
but he doesn't quite know how.

730
00:49:57.286 --> 00:49:59.163
This is A deck.

731
00:49:59.330 --> 00:50:04.251
Meanwhile. Shane Murphy
is coming down to look after the crew.

732
00:50:04.460 --> 00:50:10.382
Shane Murphy moved around the ship
a lot during those hours...

733
00:50:10.758 --> 00:50:12.843
...with great courage
and risk to himself...

734
00:50:15.012 --> 00:50:18.641
...to look after his crew
and try and find out what was going on.

735
00:50:20.809 --> 00:50:23.562
Obviously.
we've gotta compress the story...

736
00:50:23.771 --> 00:50:25.189
...into two hours.

737
00:50:25.397 --> 00:50:29.735
When. in fact. this part of the story
went on for some eight or 10 hours.

738
00:50:29.944 --> 00:50:32.530
But I think we're very true
to the central things...

739
00:50:32.738 --> 00:50:37.159
...that Perry and Murphy and the crew
are trying their best...

740
00:50:37.368 --> 00:50:42.665
...to work independently
towards a resolution.

741
00:50:42.873 --> 00:50:44.875
As is Phillips.

742
00:50:45.042 --> 00:50:46.293
It's a vegetable room.

743
00:50:47.628 --> 00:50:50.631
And. again.
this is one of those moments that...

744
00:50:51.340 --> 00:50:53.467
...if you made it up.
you wouldn't believe.

745
00:50:55.678 --> 00:51:01.850
Shane Murphy hiding in the kitchens.
almost caught by the pirates.

746
00:51:03.143 --> 00:51:08.315
Phillips. aware that he's there.
trying desperately to draw them away.

747
00:51:11.068 --> 00:51:15.322
Well. again. it deepens that sense
between Phillips and Muse.

748
00:51:17.283 --> 00:51:20.286
Something is going on between them.

749
00:51:21.704 --> 00:51:25.165
Muse knows he's lying
but he doesn't quite know how.

750
00:51:26.208 --> 00:51:28.669
Enough. Engine room.

751
00:51:28.836 --> 00:51:30.421
All right.

752
00:51:50.608 --> 00:51:53.360
- Cronan. Cronan. Do you read?
- Yeah. I got you.

753
00:51:53.527 --> 00:51:56.530
<i>They're on their way to you.
They're on their way to you.</i>

754
00:51:56.697 --> 00:51:57.740
One is barefoot.

755
00:51:57.906 --> 00:52:01.535
Is there glass you can break.
leave on the floor by the door?

756
00:52:02.620 --> 00:52:07.958
Cronan also did tremendous work
on the crew...

757
00:52:08.667 --> 00:52:11.420
...of helping to thwart the attack.

758
00:52:16.216 --> 00:52:20.596
Now. we just musically introduce
a pulse...

759
00:52:21.138 --> 00:52:25.601
...on that same distressed cello.

760
00:52:27.936 --> 00:52:32.232
It's a simple musical palette.
but I think very effective.

761
00:52:38.572 --> 00:52:44.870
Again. Mike Perry's journey that day
was extremely dangerous.

762
00:52:45.996 --> 00:52:48.582
He had to find a way
of turning off the power...

763
00:52:49.958 --> 00:52:51.710
...of the emergency generator...

764
00:52:52.961 --> 00:52:56.173
...to make it harder for the pirates
to find the crew.

765
00:52:57.549 --> 00:53:02.054
- Who did this?
- Nobody. It was just a dumb accident.

766
00:53:02.221 --> 00:53:05.557
We should get that looked at.
There's a kit in the control room.

767
00:53:05.724 --> 00:53:08.644
Quiet. Irish. You think I am stupid?

768
00:53:08.811 --> 00:53:10.437
I know what's going on.

769
00:53:10.604 --> 00:53:14.858
We're going to search this whole room.
All of it. Now go.

770
00:53:15.859 --> 00:53:17.444
Go.

771
00:53:19.655 --> 00:53:23.158
A lot of this film involves...

772
00:53:23.992 --> 00:53:27.413
...delaying moments.

773
00:53:27.830 --> 00:53:29.748
I think you know with a film like this...

774
00:53:29.957 --> 00:53:33.335
...that it's going to get
progressively more violent...

775
00:53:33.544 --> 00:53:36.505
...progressively more tense.

776
00:53:36.714 --> 00:53:41.009
But you need to believably hold it up.

777
00:53:43.470 --> 00:53:46.807
I think part of the enjoyment
of the film...

778
00:53:47.975 --> 00:53:52.855
...is in living those moments
when it is interrupted.

779
00:53:53.063 --> 00:53:57.192
When the conclusion is withheld
from you.

780
00:54:00.612 --> 00:54:02.614
Check the other side.

781
00:54:02.781 --> 00:54:05.159
There's no one here.

782
00:54:05.325 --> 00:54:07.494
Please. let's go back.

783
00:54:10.456 --> 00:54:12.249
I love the physicality of this space.

784
00:54:12.458 --> 00:54:14.877
The engine room
was an endlessly fascinating place.

785
00:54:15.085 --> 00:54:19.673
Immense cathedral of engineering.

786
00:54:21.258 --> 00:54:22.676
They're coming. Get ready.

787
00:54:22.885 --> 00:54:27.097
But brutal. brutal physical space.

788
00:54:39.276 --> 00:54:42.196
Keep going. Move.

789
00:54:42.404 --> 00:54:46.825
This is one of those moments when
the pace starts to step up a little bit.

790
00:54:47.826 --> 00:54:51.663
You don't wanna push it.
you don't wanna let it push.

791
00:54:52.080 --> 00:54:56.877
If anything.
the action is dragging the film with it...

792
00:54:57.085 --> 00:55:01.465
...rather than the film pushing the action.
which I think is as it should be.

793
00:55:02.216 --> 00:55:05.177
- We just--
- Look at me. Irish. Look at me.

794
00:55:10.766 --> 00:55:14.853
Now. the removal of the power.
the emergency generator...

795
00:55:15.062 --> 00:55:16.396
...creates another moment...

796
00:55:16.605 --> 00:55:19.191
...another intimate moment
between Phillips and Muse...

797
00:55:19.399 --> 00:55:23.403
...which is very important. I think.
for their unfolding relationship.

798
00:55:23.612 --> 00:55:25.489
- I don't know.
- Was that you?

799
00:55:25.656 --> 00:55:27.533
- I don't know what went wrong.
- No.

800
00:55:27.699 --> 00:55:31.495
You'll never find this crew.
not without any power on the ship.

801
00:55:31.662 --> 00:55:34.164
You'll never find them.
We'll never find them.

802
00:55:35.123 --> 00:55:36.708
Irish...

803
00:55:37.334 --> 00:55:39.002
...I will find.

804
00:55:40.754 --> 00:55:42.297
Not with him.

805
00:55:43.215 --> 00:55:45.008
Look. He's gonna bleed to death.

806
00:55:45.175 --> 00:55:47.594
Look. man. get us out of here.

807
00:55:48.595 --> 00:55:51.056
The cinematographer on this film
was Barry Ackroyd.

808
00:55:51.265 --> 00:55:54.268
Barry and I have worked together
many times.

809
00:55:58.564 --> 00:56:02.901
I think the job he did was quite superb.

810
00:56:04.653 --> 00:56:10.450
I don't think I've ever put a DOP
in as many contorted positions...

811
00:56:10.659 --> 00:56:13.078
...inside a skiff. inside the lifeboat...

812
00:56:14.288 --> 00:56:16.331
...even in this engine room.

813
00:56:18.250 --> 00:56:22.546
But every problem that I threw at him.
he solved triumphantly.

814
00:56:22.754 --> 00:56:27.134
I mean. these are very.
very. very low-light conditions.

815
00:56:27.342 --> 00:56:30.012
Don't talk. Go.

816
00:56:30.220 --> 00:56:33.682
Trying to make it work
and keep it natural...

817
00:56:35.100 --> 00:56:37.811
...is a very. very hard job.

818
00:56:42.482 --> 00:56:45.152
Your friend make fool of us?

819
00:56:45.319 --> 00:56:47.863
I love these faces there.

820
00:56:51.325 --> 00:56:54.953
I think the company of actors
were very. very focused.

821
00:56:55.162 --> 00:56:56.413
And I think...

822
00:56:58.624 --> 00:57:04.379
...the actors who played the crew created
another whole character. I think.

823
00:57:06.340 --> 00:57:08.258
Collectively.

824
00:57:11.219 --> 00:57:13.347
Time for a bit more khat chewing.

825
00:57:20.979 --> 00:57:25.108
Once again.
very. very low-light conditions in here.

826
00:57:25.901 --> 00:57:29.237
And Chris Rouse built the tension up...

827
00:57:30.948 --> 00:57:33.700
...trying to keep the geography clear.

828
00:57:54.930 --> 00:57:58.141
I love also the sound here.

829
00:57:58.767 --> 00:58:05.357
A ship down in the engine room
really does creak.

830
00:58:05.857 --> 00:58:08.944
They actually do sound
like ghost ships...

831
00:58:09.945 --> 00:58:12.114
...eerie and menacing.

832
00:58:12.781 --> 00:58:15.367
A great place to stage a fight.

833
00:58:15.742 --> 00:58:17.244
Hey.

834
00:58:24.835 --> 00:58:26.712
We got a problem.

835
00:58:27.170 --> 00:58:29.089
Your buddy's hurt real bad.

836
00:58:29.297 --> 00:58:32.384
We actually didn't have a lot of money
on this film.

837
00:58:34.553 --> 00:58:38.473
It was a sort of modestly budgeted film.
but it--

838
00:58:38.682 --> 00:58:42.728
I think one of the things
that I'm most pleased about the film...

839
00:58:42.936 --> 00:58:46.815
...is that I think we managed
to create sequences...

840
00:58:47.024 --> 00:58:52.320
...that looked much bigger than that.
and we did it. I think. by being--

841
00:58:52.654 --> 00:58:55.991
Spending our money
by being very. very well-prepared...

842
00:58:56.450 --> 00:59:01.288
...and I think by shooting
the action pieces very quickly.

843
00:59:03.373 --> 00:59:04.875
- Hey.
- No.

844
00:59:05.042 --> 00:59:06.418
<i>We have your leader.</i>

845
00:59:06.585 --> 00:59:09.713
We have your captain and his weapon.
We wanna trade.

846
00:59:09.880 --> 00:59:11.965
Captain for captain. We want a deal.

847
00:59:12.132 --> 00:59:15.469
Take that off of his head.
Cronan. take that <i>off</i> his head now.

848
00:59:15.635 --> 00:59:16.762
I no kill.

849
00:59:16.928 --> 00:59:18.263
Talk. Talk to your friends...

850
00:59:18.430 --> 00:59:20.432
One of the things
I remember most clearly...

851
00:59:20.640 --> 00:59:24.269
...when I read Billy Ray's script...

852
00:59:25.270 --> 00:59:27.064
...I didn't really remember the story.

853
00:59:27.272 --> 00:59:29.566
I mean. I vaguely remembered
that it happened...

854
00:59:29.775 --> 00:59:31.693
...but I knew none of the details.

855
00:59:32.986 --> 00:59:35.072
I remember when I read this...

856
00:59:36.615 --> 00:59:41.745
...that the crew had successfully taken
the pirate captain hostage...

857
00:59:44.206 --> 00:59:50.629
...and then offered to trade.
which is such an amazing story point.

858
00:59:51.004 --> 00:59:52.047
And in fact...

859
00:59:53.590 --> 00:59:55.592
...when we made the film...

860
00:59:55.801 --> 00:59:59.554
...probably the biggest single challenge
of the film...

861
00:59:59.763 --> 01:00:03.058
...was dealing
with just simply the amount of story.

862
01:00:03.391 --> 01:00:05.936
How to boil it down and compress it...

863
01:00:06.144 --> 01:00:11.108
...in a way that felt believable
and coherent and consistent...

864
01:00:11.316 --> 01:00:13.902
...and with good narrative shape.

865
01:00:14.111 --> 01:00:18.156
And Billy and I spent
an enormous amount of time...

866
01:00:18.365 --> 01:00:21.576
...going back and forth.
with Chris Rouse.

867
01:00:21.785 --> 01:00:24.037
You know. one of the things I did...

868
01:00:24.246 --> 01:00:28.583
...was sort of approach it all as a
collective effort from the beginning...

869
01:00:28.792 --> 01:00:33.004
...to try and get the film
into the best possible shape...

870
01:00:33.213 --> 01:00:35.423
...before we started shooting...

871
01:00:35.632 --> 01:00:38.260
...and I think that really paid off.

872
01:01:00.907 --> 01:01:04.077
So now we move towards the lifeboat...

873
01:01:06.246 --> 01:01:08.957
...which comes to dominate
the last half of the film.

874
01:01:13.086 --> 01:01:16.756
And as I say. the symmetry of the film.
it's almost perfect.

875
01:01:16.965 --> 01:01:20.677
This is almost the midway point
of the film.

876
01:01:22.262 --> 01:01:23.847
The first half. as I say...

877
01:01:25.098 --> 01:01:28.310
...small pirate skiffs
attacking huge container ship.

878
01:01:29.060 --> 01:01:31.062
And then. at the midway point...

879
01:01:31.980 --> 01:01:34.858
...small lifeboat chased
by enormous war ships.

880
01:01:35.025 --> 01:01:37.277
Hey. Shane. Do you have the captain?
Where is he?

881
01:01:37.444 --> 01:01:40.280
- In the engine room.
- Bring him up so they can see him.

882
01:01:40.447 --> 01:01:41.656
- I wanna see.
- You will.

883
01:01:41.823 --> 01:01:44.576
This. I think.
is outstanding ensemble acting.

884
01:01:47.412 --> 01:01:49.164
Every single actor here...

885
01:01:52.167 --> 01:01:54.961
...utterly committed
to what they're doing...

886
01:01:56.713 --> 01:01:59.799
...to create a believable.
intense scenario.

887
01:01:59.966 --> 01:02:01.551
You get in. you buckle up.

888
01:02:01.718 --> 01:02:05.013
We drop you in. and then
you're on your way. Okay? Okay?

889
01:02:05.180 --> 01:02:09.017
No. You come with us.
Till we get our guy back.

890
01:02:10.727 --> 01:02:13.438
Now we're moving to. of course...

891
01:02:14.940 --> 01:02:18.360
...the fateful moment
where Phillips goes into the lifeboat.

892
01:02:21.112 --> 01:02:26.201
What was important to me
was not to portray that moment...

893
01:02:26.409 --> 01:02:28.620
...as a sort of
Hollywood hero's moment.

894
01:02:29.955 --> 01:02:31.373
Nobody willingly...

895
01:02:33.667 --> 01:02:38.838
...goes in with four ruthless. armed.
desperate young men...

896
01:02:39.047 --> 01:02:40.173
...with nothing to lose.

897
01:02:41.758 --> 01:02:46.096
And I'm sure Phillips didn't.
I'm sure he went in as we portray it...

898
01:02:46.304 --> 01:02:51.017
...because that was the only way
he was gonna get them <i>off</i> the ship...

899
01:02:53.019 --> 01:02:58.566
...and to ensure the safety of his ship.
his crew and his cargo.

900
01:02:58.775 --> 01:03:02.279
There was no other choice.
but it wasn't something he wanted.

901
01:03:02.612 --> 01:03:04.739
But it's extremely brave. nonetheless.

902
01:03:05.490 --> 01:03:08.451
- You got a squawk box.
- Gas. gas. Enough gas?

903
01:03:08.618 --> 01:03:10.829
Plenty of fuel to get you to Somalia.

904
01:03:10.996 --> 01:03:15.000
- <i>Cap. we got the guy.</i>
- All right. Send him on in. I'm coming out.

905
01:03:15.166 --> 01:03:18.211
Okay. send him in. Let him go.

906
01:03:19.170 --> 01:03:20.505
Let him go!

907
01:03:20.672 --> 01:03:23.300
The score.
sort of underpinning this now...

908
01:03:23.508 --> 01:03:27.470
...just not pushing hard.
just sitting there.

909
01:03:27.679 --> 01:03:31.891
You gotta pump it. one. two.
three. four. five. and then you drop.

910
01:03:32.100 --> 01:03:34.060
<i>Cap. come on out.</i>

911
01:03:36.146 --> 01:03:39.774
And then they come face-to-face again.
Muse and Phillips.

912
01:03:41.359 --> 01:03:43.486
Now it's gonna be different.

913
01:03:43.653 --> 01:03:46.114
- -Pump it. then you're in the water.
and off you go.

914
01:03:49.075 --> 01:03:50.702
Go!

915
01:03:51.870 --> 01:03:53.371
Go back!

916
01:03:55.165 --> 01:03:56.499
Hey. Cap!

917
01:04:06.968 --> 01:04:12.849
It was a spectacular thing
to watch the launch of the lifeboat.

918
01:04:13.183 --> 01:04:17.062
Apparently.
if you're on a large container ship...

919
01:04:17.270 --> 01:04:21.066
...you have to practise it as a drill
at least once every six months. I think.

920
01:04:21.274 --> 01:04:24.527
All the crew have to get into the lifeboat
and launch it.

921
01:04:25.487 --> 01:04:28.281
A bit like going on a funfair ride.
I suppose.

922
01:04:29.074 --> 01:04:31.409
A bit more brutal. perhaps.

923
01:04:42.629 --> 01:04:48.385
So now we move
to the military responders.

924
01:04:48.593 --> 01:04:51.012
Task Force 151. which is the count--

925
01:04:51.221 --> 01:04:56.184
International multilateral
counter-piracy...

926
01:04:56.893 --> 01:04:58.478
...naval effort.

927
01:04:58.895 --> 01:05:00.313
Many nations.

928
01:05:03.066 --> 01:05:06.444
The call came into the <i>Bainbridge...</i>

929
01:05:07.779 --> 01:05:12.909
...and the captain of the <i>Bainbridge.</i>
Captain Frank Castellano.

930
01:05:14.536 --> 01:05:17.997
<i>Four men have taken the ship's captain
hostage in a lifeboat.</i>

931
01:05:18.164 --> 01:05:20.583
<i>Presumed Somali pirates. Over.</i>

932
01:05:20.917 --> 01:05:23.670
Roger. ma'am.
Do we have any other information? Over.

933
01:05:23.837 --> 01:05:28.425
<i>Not at this time. but best guess
is they're heading for the Somali coast.</i>

934
01:05:28.591 --> 01:05:30.885
<i>Your orders are to proceed
and intercept.</i>

935
01:05:31.052 --> 01:05:34.389
<i>Further to follow. This is CTF 151 out.</i>

936
01:05:34.556 --> 01:05:36.683
So 820 miles. even at...

937
01:05:39.269 --> 01:05:43.565
...a modern warship's top speed.
that's going to be many. many hours...

938
01:05:43.773 --> 01:05:47.819
...before the <i>Bainbridge</i> can get there
to provide any help.

939
01:05:47.986 --> 01:05:51.281
Bridge. captain. full left rudder.
Come to course 285.

940
01:06:07.505 --> 01:06:09.924
One of the discussions...

941
01:06:10.133 --> 01:06:13.636
...that Billy Ray. who wrote the
screenplay. and myself had early on...

942
01:06:13.845 --> 01:06:15.597
...was about the lifeboat scenes.

943
01:06:15.805 --> 01:06:17.849
I think it was one of the areas that we...

944
01:06:18.892 --> 01:06:21.478
...agreed most profoundly on.

945
01:06:21.936 --> 01:06:24.314
We used to joke afterwards
that we disagreed...

946
01:06:24.522 --> 01:06:27.901
...about everything on this film
except the most important things.

947
01:06:28.693 --> 01:06:33.615
And one of the most important things
was that we both believed...

948
01:06:33.823 --> 01:06:38.161
...that we should not. in this film.
short-change the lifeboat scenes.

949
01:06:38.369 --> 01:06:41.206
It was something
Billy felt very strongly about...

950
01:06:41.414 --> 01:06:44.000
...and I totally agreed.
and he was totally right.

951
01:06:44.209 --> 01:06:50.548
It was crucial for this film
that when you inhabited the lifeboat...

952
01:06:50.757 --> 01:06:56.471
...that you didn't feel suddenly
that time was starting to telescope.

953
01:06:56.679 --> 01:07:01.434
On the contrary.
I think you need to feel...

954
01:07:01.643 --> 01:07:03.853
...that it was an agony of waiting.

955
01:07:04.062 --> 01:07:05.730
It was going to be an ordeal.

956
01:07:07.106 --> 01:07:12.570
And how were these characters
in this confined space--

957
01:07:12.779 --> 01:07:17.033
Richard Phillips
and his four captors.

958
01:07:17.242 --> 01:07:19.827
- -How were they going to react...

959
01:07:20.036 --> 01:07:25.333
...in the furnace of a small lifeboat
on the Indian Ocean?

960
01:07:25.542 --> 01:07:29.087
Unbearable heat. swell.

961
01:07:29.295 --> 01:07:31.673
Just a physical ordeal.

962
01:07:31.881 --> 01:07:35.385
And most of all. could they be caught?

963
01:07:35.593 --> 01:07:38.846
Because in the end.
the structure of the film. at this point...

964
01:07:39.222 --> 01:07:41.057
...is a race.

965
01:07:41.266 --> 01:07:46.020
They're trying to race in this
small five-mile-an-hour lifeboat...

966
01:07:46.229 --> 01:07:49.566
...to the coast
a couple of hundred miles away...

967
01:07:49.774 --> 01:07:51.401
...before any...

968
01:07:53.111 --> 01:07:57.031
...counter-piracy vessel
can get to them to intercept.

969
01:07:57.240 --> 01:07:58.908
It's a gift.

970
01:08:05.540 --> 01:08:07.083
Hey.

971
01:08:09.794 --> 01:08:11.671
Irish.

972
01:08:11.838 --> 01:08:15.800
You lie. Irish. Your ship no broke.

973
01:08:15.967 --> 01:08:17.844
They come Somalia too.

974
01:08:18.011 --> 01:08:19.304
Going back...

975
01:08:19.512 --> 01:08:21.222
...to the discussion earlier...

976
01:08:21.389 --> 01:08:23.808
...where I was saying
that one of the things I like--

977
01:08:24.017 --> 01:08:28.521
Liked about the story was that
everybody was always telling...

978
01:08:28.730 --> 01:08:31.774
...less than the truth to everybody else.

979
01:08:31.983 --> 01:08:34.694
And then they'd find out. you know?

980
01:08:34.902 --> 01:08:37.655
Phillips had spent
a tremendous amount of time...

981
01:08:37.864 --> 01:08:41.701
...when he was on the bridge
telling Muse that the ship had broken.

982
01:08:41.909 --> 01:08:44.537
But of course that was a lie...

983
01:08:44.746 --> 01:08:48.666
...and as soon as the <i>Alabama</i>
gave chase. Muse knew it.

984
01:08:50.001 --> 01:08:53.630
But of course.
Muse was busy lying...

985
01:08:53.838 --> 01:08:57.050
...to Phillips as well.
telling him it was gonna be all right.

986
01:09:00.887 --> 01:09:02.889
Give me some khat.

987
01:09:03.056 --> 01:09:05.391
Why?
You've had more than your share.

988
01:09:05.558 --> 01:09:07.644
Says who? Give me some more!

989
01:09:07.810 --> 01:09:09.103
Shut up!

990
01:09:09.270 --> 01:09:11.356
Both of you. shut up.

991
01:09:11.522 --> 01:09:13.066
Just take it.

992
01:09:13.274 --> 01:09:16.694
These four young men
were obsessed with khat.

993
01:09:17.570 --> 01:09:21.074
As I said earlier...

994
01:09:21.282 --> 01:09:24.452
...it's chewed ubiquitously...

995
01:09:24.661 --> 01:09:26.871
...in that part of Africa.

996
01:09:30.792 --> 01:09:34.671
And one of the realities
of this experience was that...

997
01:09:34.879 --> 01:09:37.965
...when the khat started to run out.
as it did...

998
01:09:38.675 --> 01:09:41.594
...the pressure
and the tension began to grow.

999
01:09:41.761 --> 01:09:45.431
This money. taking you. that's all it is.

1000
01:09:45.640 --> 01:09:48.559
You come to our waters. you got to pay.

1001
01:09:48.726 --> 01:09:51.646
We were in international waters.

1002
01:09:51.813 --> 01:09:53.815
Not your waters. international waters.

1003
01:09:53.981 --> 01:09:55.858
Somali pirates always say that--

1004
01:09:56.067 --> 01:09:58.986
Two things. I think. are common
to all Somali pirates.

1005
01:09:59.195 --> 01:10:03.991
They will always tell you that the money
that they're trying to get is just taxes.

1006
01:10:04.200 --> 01:10:07.203
And the other is
that they're just fishermen.

1007
01:10:08.413 --> 01:10:11.290
One of the things that was interesting.
studying the subject...

1008
01:10:11.499 --> 01:10:13.543
...was that there's no question...

1009
01:10:14.043 --> 01:10:19.298
...that the modern rise
of Somali piracy definitely...

1010
01:10:19.674 --> 01:10:23.761
...was a response to over-fishing
and toxic-waste dumping...

1011
01:10:23.970 --> 01:10:25.513
...off the coast of Somalia.

1012
01:10:25.722 --> 01:10:31.728
As Somalia collapsed into civil war
and there was no central government...

1013
01:10:31.936 --> 01:10:34.772
...there was no attempt to police...

1014
01:10:35.606 --> 01:10:37.024
...the coasts.

1015
01:10:37.233 --> 01:10:38.735
And. of course...

1016
01:10:40.194 --> 01:10:43.614
...fishing vessels
over-fished and dumped.

1017
01:10:43.823 --> 01:10:47.952
And local fishing communities
began to strike back.

1018
01:10:48.161 --> 01:10:52.623
That was in the '80s and early '90s. Very
quickly. once money started to be made...

1019
01:10:52.832 --> 01:10:57.503
...the warlords and the gangsters moved
in. and by the time of these events...

1020
01:10:57.712 --> 01:11:01.174
...piracy had become
highly organised.

1021
01:11:01.382 --> 01:11:03.342
International...

1022
01:11:03.926 --> 01:11:06.095
...organised crime.

1023
01:11:07.346 --> 01:11:11.517
But many of the young men...

1024
01:11:12.059 --> 01:11:13.978
...involved...

1025
01:11:14.771 --> 01:11:18.900
...liked to talk about themselves...

1026
01:11:19.275 --> 01:11:21.194
...as just fishermen.

1027
01:11:24.280 --> 01:11:26.240
Not true. of course. but...

1028
01:11:27.450 --> 01:11:30.536
But a necessary fiction. perhaps.

1029
01:11:39.420 --> 01:11:43.174
Go ahead. come here. It's all right.
Your foot. Give me your foot.

1030
01:11:43.341 --> 01:11:44.550
Come on.

1031
01:11:45.593 --> 01:11:47.762
This scene. I think. beautifully played...

1032
01:11:47.970 --> 01:11:50.765
...because it's starting to develop...

1033
01:11:51.140 --> 01:11:53.726
...the crucial relationships
inside the boat--

1034
01:11:53.935 --> 01:11:56.813
Inside the lifeboat. between...

1035
01:11:57.522 --> 01:12:00.608
...Tom and Bilal. the youngest pirate.

1036
01:12:01.651 --> 01:12:03.319
And of course...

1037
01:12:03.986 --> 01:12:06.113
...with Najee...

1038
01:12:07.448 --> 01:12:09.116
...the most dangerous of the four.

1039
01:12:15.456 --> 01:12:18.459
Slowly but surely. the relationship
between Phillips and Najee...

1040
01:12:18.668 --> 01:12:21.087
...comes to dominate the film.

1041
01:12:22.004 --> 01:12:25.132
And that process takes a big step...

1042
01:12:25.633 --> 01:12:27.593
...in this scene.

1043
01:12:28.344 --> 01:12:31.305
Go back. Get back there.

1044
01:12:41.232 --> 01:12:44.360
But of course.
the challenge for Muse is...

1045
01:12:44.861 --> 01:12:46.320
...what does he do?

1046
01:12:46.529 --> 01:12:49.824
Is he is charge or is Najee in charge?

1047
01:12:53.786 --> 01:12:56.581
And which policy is most likely...

1048
01:12:56.789 --> 01:13:00.668
...to give them a successful outcome in
their own terms. to get the hijack money.

1049
01:13:00.877 --> 01:13:03.963
That's really the question
of the second half of the film.

1050
01:13:04.171 --> 01:13:06.591
Who is in charge. Muse?

1051
01:13:16.100 --> 01:13:17.727
So meanwhile...

1052
01:13:17.935 --> 01:13:22.690
...the military response
starts to take shape.

1053
01:13:22.899 --> 01:13:25.026
First of all...

1054
01:13:25.234 --> 01:13:28.446
...the lifeboat's
put under aerial surveillance.

1055
01:13:29.739 --> 01:13:31.532
And that material...

1056
01:13:31.741 --> 01:13:34.911
...and other intelligence material
is relayed to the <i>Bainbridge...</i>

1057
01:13:35.119 --> 01:13:38.789
...so that Captain Castellano
is in the best position...

1058
01:13:38.998 --> 01:13:43.002
...to formulate a strategy
as to what to do when he arrives...

1059
01:13:43.210 --> 01:13:45.755
...and intercepts the lifeboat.

1060
01:13:45.922 --> 01:13:49.675
<i>According to ONI. that vessel's under
the control of Somali warlord Garaad.</i>

1061
01:13:49.884 --> 01:13:52.678
<i>We're working on getting the IDs
of the kidnappers.</i>

1062
01:13:52.845 --> 01:13:57.016
If this is Garaad's guys. they're looking
for a payday. which means they'll talk.

1063
01:13:57.183 --> 01:14:00.144
If we can get them talking.
we can wear them down. Over.

1064
01:14:00.311 --> 01:14:02.605
All these scenes were shot...

1065
01:14:03.314 --> 01:14:05.691
...on the <i>USS Truxtun...</i>

1066
01:14:05.900 --> 01:14:08.694
...which was the sister ship
of the <i>Bainbridge.</i>

1067
01:14:08.903 --> 01:14:10.863
And...

1068
01:14:11.530 --> 01:14:14.617
...with the exception of Yul here...

1069
01:14:14.825 --> 01:14:18.955
...a lot of these men and women
are the crew of the <i>Truxtun...</i>

1070
01:14:19.163 --> 01:14:23.709
...without whose support we would never
have been able to convey...

1071
01:14:23.918 --> 01:14:28.130
...the reality of these command posts.

1072
01:14:29.006 --> 01:14:32.259
<i>If you haven't gotten Phillips back
by the time they arrive...</i>

1073
01:14:32.426 --> 01:14:34.011
<i>...the SEALs will take care of it.</i>

1074
01:14:34.178 --> 01:14:37.139
And again. one of the things
you've got to do...

1075
01:14:37.348 --> 01:14:41.894
...I think.
if you're gonna convey downrange...

1076
01:14:42.061 --> 01:14:46.524
...real audience involvement.
is to take your time now...

1077
01:14:46.691 --> 01:14:50.277
...to show people how
that control room works.

1078
01:14:51.278 --> 01:14:55.783
Who are the dominant characters?
What are the procedures in there?

1079
01:14:55.992 --> 01:15:00.121
And I think that all
starts to pay off dividends later.

1080
01:15:12.049 --> 01:15:17.430
The heat inside that lifeboat
must have been unbearable.

1081
01:15:18.514 --> 01:15:20.599
The motion too.

1082
01:15:22.018 --> 01:15:24.729
When we first started shooting
on the lifeboat...

1083
01:15:24.895 --> 01:15:27.314
...off the coast of Malta...

1084
01:15:27.481 --> 01:15:32.361
...within half an hour we had two
or three people physically sick...

1085
01:15:32.611 --> 01:15:38.826
...from the turbulence inside.

1086
01:15:38.993 --> 01:15:41.746
What it must have been like
for four or five days...

1087
01:15:42.747 --> 01:15:45.041
...I just can't imagine.

1088
01:15:45.207 --> 01:15:48.210
It literally must have been
a hell on Earth.

1089
01:15:51.338 --> 01:15:53.215
And of course...

1090
01:15:55.051 --> 01:15:57.845
...tempers soon get frayed.

1091
01:16:05.227 --> 01:16:06.812
Hey. Hey.

1092
01:16:08.397 --> 01:16:11.108
That's enough.

1093
01:16:11.275 --> 01:16:13.861
Take it away.

1094
01:16:14.028 --> 01:16:16.363
From now on this water is only for us.

1095
01:16:17.281 --> 01:16:21.619
This scene's an important scene
because it really brings Muse...

1096
01:16:21.786 --> 01:16:22.828
...into the picture.

1097
01:16:22.995 --> 01:16:27.124
What is he going to do.
knowing as he does...

1098
01:16:27.583 --> 01:16:30.544
...that Najee is starting...

1099
01:16:31.253 --> 01:16:33.589
...to lose control.

1100
01:16:35.132 --> 01:16:37.426
And of course...

1101
01:16:37.802 --> 01:16:42.431
...you can see in Phillips's eyes there.
in Tom's look. that he knows...

1102
01:16:42.598 --> 01:16:44.475
...that Muse's got a problem.

1103
01:16:44.809 --> 01:16:47.895
And he's watching and watching
and watching...

1104
01:16:48.187 --> 01:16:51.649
...and now he tries
to manipulate Muse...

1105
01:16:51.816 --> 01:16:54.944
...to use his problems against him.

1106
01:16:55.528 --> 01:16:59.240
And that's part of the battle of wills
between the two of them.

1107
01:17:00.908 --> 01:17:03.327
I know what I'm doing.

1108
01:17:03.911 --> 01:17:06.997
Yeah. yeah. sure. you do. Of course.
You're the captain now.

1109
01:17:07.164 --> 01:17:11.377
Tom. I think. is a magnificent...

1110
01:17:12.378 --> 01:17:14.046
...player of the everyman.

1111
01:17:14.213 --> 01:17:17.341
The way he inhabits this role...

1112
01:17:17.550 --> 01:17:20.511
...and brings all the colours out...

1113
01:17:20.678 --> 01:17:26.976
...but in a simple. very real register...

1114
01:17:27.143 --> 01:17:29.520
...is magnificent.

1115
01:17:32.481 --> 01:17:37.319
Just that constant watching.
that constant feeling that he's--

1116
01:17:37.570 --> 01:17:44.243
Although he's helpless. he's looking
for any small opportunity he can...

1117
01:17:44.535 --> 01:17:47.163
...to manipulate the situation.

1118
01:17:52.877 --> 01:17:54.920
Brilliant acting.

1119
01:18:07.558 --> 01:18:10.227
We should be heading northwest.

1120
01:18:10.394 --> 01:18:13.439
We've got to get to Garaad's port.

1121
01:18:13.606 --> 01:18:16.066
I am. but there's a lot of wind.

1122
01:18:16.233 --> 01:18:18.402
- Just go!
- Okay. then let me do it.

1123
01:18:21.197 --> 01:18:25.451
It's the same principle really.
as with the first and second attack.

1124
01:18:25.618 --> 01:18:29.580
You mustn't hurry the film.

1125
01:18:32.124 --> 01:18:37.796
I think the power of the film
lies in really inhabiting the lifeboat.

1126
01:18:39.673 --> 01:18:44.136
So you feel as Phillips does.

1127
01:18:45.054 --> 01:18:49.934
How can he turn this situation
to his vantage. or can he?

1128
01:18:50.809 --> 01:18:53.687
- <i>-Or don't come back at all.</i>

1129
01:18:58.275 --> 01:19:01.237
Sounds like there's a problem.
Is there a problem?

1130
01:19:02.821 --> 01:19:04.615
Problem.

1131
01:19:05.741 --> 01:19:08.035
No problem. Irish.

1132
01:19:08.619 --> 01:19:11.247
Everything gonna be okay.

1133
01:19:11.997 --> 01:19:17.044
Barkhad Abdi is brilliant. I think.
in this scene too. because he...

1134
01:19:18.254 --> 01:19:19.838
He tries to brush him off...

1135
01:19:20.005 --> 01:19:22.216
...but you know the pressure's
building on him.

1136
01:19:22.383 --> 01:19:25.219
Bainbridge <i>CO has until your arrival
to negotiate a surrender.</i>

1137
01:19:25.386 --> 01:19:27.721
<i>But upon boarding.
you will assume command.</i>

1138
01:19:28.681 --> 01:19:34.687
Now we get another piece in the
unfolding story of the military response.

1139
01:19:34.937 --> 01:19:39.817
As the SEAL Team 6 are mobilised.

1140
01:19:39.984 --> 01:19:44.029
But of course it's gonna take them
many. many hours to get there.

1141
01:19:47.866 --> 01:19:50.786
But obviously each step down that road...

1142
01:19:51.620 --> 01:19:54.623
...raises the stakes inside the lifeboat.

1143
01:20:03.340 --> 01:20:05.509
It's almost as if...

1144
01:20:05.676 --> 01:20:08.137
...the most dangerous thing.
if you're a hostage...

1145
01:20:08.304 --> 01:20:10.556
...is not to be rescued...

1146
01:20:10.723 --> 01:20:14.518
...but the next most dangerous thing
is to be rescued.

1147
01:20:14.768 --> 01:20:17.313
And it's that central...

1148
01:20:19.023 --> 01:20:20.649
...terror...

1149
01:20:21.775 --> 01:20:25.195
...that this film tries to depict.

1150
01:20:25.863 --> 01:20:28.574
I can't feel my foot anymore.

1151
01:20:28.741 --> 01:20:31.160
It's like hell in here.

1152
01:20:34.163 --> 01:20:36.248
I love the way Tom...

1153
01:20:36.498 --> 01:20:40.544
...is sizing up the situation
every moment.

1154
01:20:41.545 --> 01:20:43.380
He wants air.

1155
01:20:43.547 --> 01:20:49.887
Looking at each pirate in turn.
trying to work out what's happening.

1156
01:20:57.644 --> 01:21:00.731
Talk too much. Too much.

1157
01:21:11.116 --> 01:21:14.328
It's funny. whenever I watch this film...

1158
01:21:14.620 --> 01:21:16.705
...when he opens the window.
smashes it out...

1159
01:21:16.830 --> 01:21:19.083
...I almost can feel
the draught on my face.

1160
01:21:19.249 --> 01:21:23.670
It feels so hot and claustrophobic
by this stage.

1161
01:21:24.588 --> 01:21:26.799
- -You'll get a million bottles of it.

1162
01:21:26.965 --> 01:21:30.094
- All the water you want.
- Really?

1163
01:21:32.304 --> 01:21:35.349
So this is a very important scene now...

1164
01:21:35.516 --> 01:21:38.060
...because it brings out
the triangular relationship...

1165
01:21:38.227 --> 01:21:41.105
...between Phillips. Muse and Najee.

1166
01:21:41.814 --> 01:21:46.318
And. of course. develops this idea
of everybody lying to everybody else...

1167
01:21:46.485 --> 01:21:49.655
...as Muse tells him the story...

1168
01:21:50.072 --> 01:21:52.908
...about the millions he's made
from hijacking.

1169
01:21:53.158 --> 01:21:55.702
And Phillips calls him out on it.

1170
01:21:57.996 --> 01:22:02.334
Your problem isn't me talking to you.
Your problem is you not listening.

1171
01:22:11.135 --> 01:22:14.763
You think you have any power here?

1172
01:22:14.930 --> 01:22:18.559
- Let him go.
- I should shoot you and be done.

1173
01:22:18.725 --> 01:22:20.727
Take your gun off him.

1174
01:22:20.894 --> 01:22:23.689
I'm the captain.
Who do you think you are?

1175
01:22:25.232 --> 01:22:26.984
So now...

1176
01:22:28.193 --> 01:22:29.236
...Najee throws down.

1177
01:22:37.369 --> 01:22:40.122
But before it can be resolved...

1178
01:22:42.666 --> 01:22:44.835
...the <i>Bainbridge</i> arrives.

1179
01:22:46.920 --> 01:22:50.674
This was an immense challenge
to shoot this scene.

1180
01:22:52.259 --> 01:22:56.221
Bringing a modern warship very.
very close. at high speed...

1181
01:22:56.388 --> 01:22:58.724
...to a small lifeboat was no small...

1182
01:23:00.767 --> 01:23:02.811
No small endeavour.

1183
01:23:04.480 --> 01:23:09.401
But it was quite spectacular to watch
a pair of those vessels...

1184
01:23:09.568 --> 01:23:14.406
...and the wake they create.
Enormous. enormous waves.

1185
01:23:18.368 --> 01:23:22.789
I love what Tom does here.
You see the elation...

1186
01:23:22.956 --> 01:23:25.709
...and the terror all mixed up in one.

1187
01:23:25.918 --> 01:23:28.170
Get something to tie the doors.

1188
01:23:29.296 --> 01:23:31.465
<i>Alabama</i> lifeboat.
this is Frank Castellano...

1189
01:23:31.590 --> 01:23:33.759
...commander of the <i>USS Bainbridge.</i>

1190
01:23:33.967 --> 01:23:38.096
We wanna get Captain Phillips back
safely and end this thing peacefully.

1191
01:23:39.389 --> 01:23:42.476
We worked a long time
to get the score right here.

1192
01:23:44.019 --> 01:23:48.607
And it was a question of finding...

1193
01:23:50.275 --> 01:23:53.862
...some piece where the score could sit
but would...

1194
01:23:55.155 --> 01:23:57.115
...have some drive...

1195
01:23:57.699 --> 01:24:02.829
...but not push too hard and allow us
to bring brass through.

1196
01:24:02.996 --> 01:24:09.378
But Henry ended up with this
very simple little ostinato.

1197
01:24:11.129 --> 01:24:13.006
Very. very powerful.

1198
01:24:13.173 --> 01:24:15.759
<i>We just want to talk.</i>

1199
01:24:16.718 --> 01:24:20.514
Made me think. occasionally.
that I made a film...

1200
01:24:20.681 --> 01:24:23.976
...that felt a bit like
<i>Assault on Precinct 13.</i>

1201
01:24:24.142 --> 01:24:28.021
It's got the same musical sense.
which I love. incidentally...

1202
01:24:28.188 --> 01:24:32.317
...because I love that movie.
I think it's a brilliant film.

1203
01:24:32.734 --> 01:24:37.781
There's something about that ostinato
that made me think of it.

1204
01:24:37.948 --> 01:24:41.159
No tricks. or your captain dead.

1205
01:24:47.040 --> 01:24:53.714
I love Tom's look here. and the way
that Chris picks up Castellano's look.

1206
01:24:54.423 --> 01:25:00.470
One look pulling you to the other.
binding characters in. building tension.

1207
01:25:01.805 --> 01:25:03.473
- Shane Murphy?
- Yeah. that's me.

1208
01:25:03.640 --> 01:25:07.352
Lieutenant Hicks. You're entering
a military engagement zone. sir.

1209
01:25:07.519 --> 01:25:12.608
Need you to bring the ship left to 210.
We are here to escort you to Mombasa.

1210
01:25:12.774 --> 01:25:15.235
Your captain'll be in good hands.

1211
01:25:15.402 --> 01:25:17.821
All right. You heard him. guys.

1212
01:25:18.030 --> 01:25:21.325
One of the structural problems
of the story. of course...

1213
01:25:21.491 --> 01:25:26.496
...is that the <i>Alabama</i> disappears
at this stage. from the story.

1214
01:25:26.663 --> 01:25:33.128
And we wrestled with that problem
for a long time in advance. how to...?

1215
01:25:33.295 --> 01:25:37.758
And it's often the case in films.
you often have to wrestle...

1216
01:25:37.924 --> 01:25:41.178
...with how to lose characters
and situations in a way...

1217
01:25:41.345 --> 01:25:45.223
...that your audience
doesn't really notice or doesn't care.

1218
01:25:47.059 --> 01:25:52.856
And it was about doing it in a way
that you bait and switch and move on...

1219
01:25:53.815 --> 01:25:56.610
...to develop the drama in the lifeboat.

1220
01:25:56.777 --> 01:26:03.200
And now. from here on in. the story
becomes the story of the lifeboat...

1221
01:26:03.367 --> 01:26:04.951
...versus the military.

1222
01:26:05.535 --> 01:26:07.746
Irish. your crew...

1223
01:26:08.872 --> 01:26:10.374
...run.

1224
01:26:10.540 --> 01:26:11.625
Ship go.

1225
01:26:11.792 --> 01:26:13.710
Brilliant acting. I think. at this stage.

1226
01:26:14.920 --> 01:26:17.214
You better think
about what you're doing.

1227
01:26:18.965 --> 01:26:23.762
Navy good. They protect us.
Back to Somalia.

1228
01:26:23.929 --> 01:26:26.473
The Navy's not here to protect you.

1229
01:26:28.016 --> 01:26:30.018
Bravado from Muse.

1230
01:26:30.977 --> 01:26:32.896
No choice.

1231
01:26:33.438 --> 01:26:34.523
I got you.

1232
01:26:34.815 --> 01:26:38.485
You know the situation
is inherently unstable.

1233
01:26:47.953 --> 01:26:50.455
Just that one shot shows you.
in a nutshell. I think...

1234
01:26:50.622 --> 01:26:52.708
...the difficulties Barry
had to contend with.

1235
01:26:52.874 --> 01:26:58.964
How do you get images on the water
when you're in small craft that are...

1236
01:27:00.966 --> 01:27:03.969
...you know. sufficiently stable
that you can understand them?

1237
01:27:04.136 --> 01:27:06.263
It's a big. big. big problem.

1238
01:27:07.055 --> 01:27:10.726
People sometimes criticise me
for the shaky cam.

1239
01:27:10.892 --> 01:27:15.522
I'd love to bring those people out
onto the ocean in a 4-foot swell...

1240
01:27:15.689 --> 01:27:20.277
...and say. "Well. how exactly
would you get stable images?"

1241
01:27:21.611 --> 01:27:24.698
The wonder is that we had any images
at all. to be honest.

1242
01:27:24.906 --> 01:27:28.535
Okay. Wait.

1243
01:27:28.702 --> 01:27:31.079
To me. this...

1244
01:27:31.705 --> 01:27:35.041
...is very. very real. very intense.

1245
01:27:35.208 --> 01:27:40.172
And you start to feel
the different ways...

1246
01:27:40.338 --> 01:27:42.966
...these four young men
are responding.

1247
01:27:44.092 --> 01:27:45.844
How Phillips is responding.

1248
01:27:46.553 --> 01:27:51.433
And the problem from the
anti-piracy task force's point of view.

1249
01:27:51.600 --> 01:27:54.895
How do they resolve
this situation peacefully?

1250
01:27:56.062 --> 01:27:58.231
I'm in Seat 15.

1251
01:27:58.398 --> 01:28:00.066
You understand?

1252
01:28:00.567 --> 01:28:02.486
<i>I'm in Seat 15.</i>

1253
01:28:02.652 --> 01:28:04.696
All stations. TAO. log it: Seat 15.

1254
01:28:04.863 --> 01:28:08.074
Break. CICWO. TAO.
Send that to CTF 151 and SOCOM.

1255
01:28:09.701 --> 01:28:11.661
Don't worry. sir. We'll handle it.

1256
01:28:11.870 --> 01:28:13.413
Get him back inside.

1257
01:28:14.623 --> 01:28:17.542
Again. spending time
inside the control room...

1258
01:28:18.084 --> 01:28:20.295
...to show how it works. who does what.

1259
01:28:20.504 --> 01:28:21.755
Where's the money?

1260
01:28:21.922 --> 01:28:25.133
<i>I don't want your food.
I want your money.</i>

1261
01:28:25.300 --> 01:28:28.386
- <i>We got another on top.</i>
- OSS. maintain camera footage.

1262
01:28:28.553 --> 01:28:30.472
- Hold on a second.
- No tricks. sahib.

1263
01:28:30.639 --> 01:28:34.601
All these vessels. as part of
the international anti-piracy patrol...

1264
01:28:34.768 --> 01:28:40.607
...have Somali speakers onboard
for these encounters.

1265
01:28:40.816 --> 01:28:43.401
They're treating us like children.

1266
01:28:43.568 --> 01:28:45.111
Ten million dollars. when?

1267
01:28:45.278 --> 01:28:46.613
It's not that easy...

1268
01:28:46.780 --> 01:28:48.740
...so we need time.

1269
01:28:49.324 --> 01:28:52.077
You can imagine how the tension rises.

1270
01:28:54.454 --> 01:28:57.999
They've got expectations
of a huge payday.

1271
01:28:59.251 --> 01:29:00.418
And. of course...

1272
01:29:01.586 --> 01:29:05.966
...what they can't understand
is that no deal can ever be done.

1273
01:29:08.343 --> 01:29:12.097
But somewhere.
on the U.S. Navy side...

1274
01:29:12.222 --> 01:29:15.100
...they need to resolve this
thing peacefully.

1275
01:29:18.019 --> 01:29:21.648
So each holds cards
that the other doesn't have.

1276
01:29:22.524 --> 01:29:24.734
It's asymmetrical.

1277
01:29:25.402 --> 01:29:27.237
But also perfectly balanced.

1278
01:29:29.155 --> 01:29:34.202
Four young men with AK-47s
and nothing to lose...

1279
01:29:34.369 --> 01:29:38.290
...versus the might of the U.S. Navy.

1280
01:29:38.832 --> 01:29:40.709
It's a standoff.

1281
01:29:40.917 --> 01:29:44.087
- I say he okay.
- I need to hear it from him.

1282
01:29:48.341 --> 01:29:50.552
And. of course. caught in the middle...

1283
01:29:52.304 --> 01:29:54.180
...is Captain Phillips.

1284
01:29:55.682 --> 01:29:57.893
- Talk.
- Yeah. yeah. it's me.

1285
01:29:58.059 --> 01:29:59.394
Are you okay?

1286
01:29:59.936 --> 01:30:03.815
It's falling apart in here. He just fired
off a round next to my head.

1287
01:30:04.774 --> 01:30:08.278
- Is the leader there?
- Yeah. he can hear you.

1288
01:30:08.445 --> 01:30:11.781
<i>Captain. listen to me.
We will not tolerate this.</i>

1289
01:30:11.948 --> 01:30:15.368
<i>As captain. you're responsible
for the lives of everyone onboard.</i>

1290
01:30:15.577 --> 01:30:17.913
<i>Right now
you are putting them in jeopardy.</i>

1291
01:30:18.079 --> 01:30:20.123
We wanna resolve this thing
peacefully.

1292
01:30:21.541 --> 01:30:24.878
<i>Let's find a way out of this together
before someone gets hurt.</i>

1293
01:30:25.045 --> 01:30:28.131
Pressure on Muse now.
What's he going to do?

1294
01:30:28.924 --> 01:30:32.010
<i>Alabama</i> lifeboat. respond.

1295
01:30:34.763 --> 01:30:36.723
I talk when I go Somalia.

1296
01:30:37.641 --> 01:30:38.725
Sit down.

1297
01:30:38.892 --> 01:30:40.477
Sit down!

1298
01:30:40.936 --> 01:30:42.896
He just wants the money.

1299
01:30:43.229 --> 01:30:45.565
So he doubles the ante.
He's gonna keep on going...

1300
01:30:45.774 --> 01:30:48.693
...he's gonna keep on pushing on.
see if he can get to Somalia.

1301
01:30:49.736 --> 01:30:52.197
If he can get Phillips to Somalia...

1302
01:30:53.073 --> 01:30:58.536
...the stakes get much harder
for anyone trying to rescue him.

1303
01:30:59.704 --> 01:31:03.375
ETA on the SEAL team is 0400.

1304
01:31:05.335 --> 01:31:07.128
But from Castellano's point of view...

1305
01:31:07.337 --> 01:31:10.632
...the window of opportunity
to negotiate a peaceful outcome...

1306
01:31:10.840 --> 01:31:12.801
...is fast diminishing.

1307
01:31:15.470 --> 01:31:19.516
Military reinforcements are coming...

1308
01:31:19.975 --> 01:31:22.268
...and the SEALs are not far away.

1309
01:31:26.940 --> 01:31:30.318
Irish. no worry.

1310
01:31:31.778 --> 01:31:35.532
I think right in those two shots there.
you feel...

1311
01:31:36.616 --> 01:31:39.869
...the pressure
that both Muse and Phillips are under.

1312
01:31:40.036 --> 01:31:41.246
After this. I go America.

1313
01:31:42.580 --> 01:31:45.125
I always wanted to go America.

1314
01:31:46.001 --> 01:31:51.256
In a sense. their interests
are both served by a negotiation...

1315
01:31:52.090 --> 01:31:54.467
...not by a...

1316
01:31:56.845 --> 01:31:59.305
An unsuccessful standoff.

1317
01:31:59.889 --> 01:32:02.684
There are two more ships.
one on either side.

1318
01:32:03.935 --> 01:32:08.857
Phillips can see
that Muse is beginning to struggle.

1319
01:32:09.065 --> 01:32:13.445
His arm is being infected. he's
starting to run a big fever. he's sick.

1320
01:32:13.611 --> 01:32:15.613
Sit down! Sit down!

1321
01:32:15.780 --> 01:32:18.408
- Sit down!
- Down! Down!

1322
01:32:18.616 --> 01:32:20.702
And now Phillips
can see the reinforcements.

1323
01:32:20.910 --> 01:32:23.163
He knows what's coming.

1324
01:32:24.581 --> 01:32:27.375
And as I said earlier...

1325
01:32:27.584 --> 01:32:29.669
...the biggest danger
is not to be rescued...

1326
01:32:29.878 --> 01:32:32.338
...but the next greatest danger
is to be rescued.

1327
01:32:32.505 --> 01:32:35.133
He's gone. He's left you alone.

1328
01:32:35.759 --> 01:32:37.844
You had a plan to take my ship.

1329
01:32:37.969 --> 01:32:40.305
That didn't work.
so you thought you could take me?

1330
01:32:40.472 --> 01:32:42.223
- Shut up.
- Make a run to Somalia?

1331
01:32:42.390 --> 01:32:45.685
They got the Navy out there.
You gotta give up. You gotta stop.

1332
01:32:46.144 --> 01:32:47.604
Brilliant scene. this. I think.

1333
01:32:47.812 --> 01:32:50.065
Absolutely beautifully played
by the two of them.

1334
01:32:50.231 --> 01:32:51.858
They can't let you win.

1335
01:32:52.025 --> 01:32:55.737
They would rather sink this boat
than let you get me back to Somalia.

1336
01:32:55.904 --> 01:32:56.946
It's over.

1337
01:33:00.617 --> 01:33:02.994
I come too far. Irish.

1338
01:33:03.578 --> 01:33:07.540
I can't give up. No.

1339
01:33:16.549 --> 01:33:19.511
It's a fateful moment. I think.
between the two of them.

1340
01:33:21.096 --> 01:33:23.807
Phillips can see
he's never going to give up.

1341
01:33:31.231 --> 01:33:34.692
So the stage is set. really.
for the denouement.

1342
01:33:36.152 --> 01:33:37.529
Roger that.

1343
01:33:46.579 --> 01:33:49.999
I think Castellano.
at this point. knows...

1344
01:33:51.459 --> 01:33:54.504
...that the space and the time
and the room for negotiation...

1345
01:33:54.671 --> 01:33:56.172
...is almost at an end.

1346
01:34:02.846 --> 01:34:06.683
And I think Phillips knows it too.
And I think Muse knows it as well.

1347
01:34:14.607 --> 01:34:17.944
So now. finally.
all that watching pays off.

1348
01:34:18.194 --> 01:34:21.322
Phillips looks.
sees that Najee is sleeping.

1349
01:34:22.323 --> 01:34:24.868
Something's gonna happen
in that lifeboat.

1350
01:34:26.244 --> 01:34:29.706
But on the other side of the story.
the SEALs are inbound.

1351
01:34:29.914 --> 01:34:33.918
So the stakes are ratcheting up.

1352
01:34:39.048 --> 01:34:41.843
Phillips looks at the door...

1353
01:34:42.093 --> 01:34:44.220
...sees Bilal put his weapon down.

1354
01:34:47.390 --> 01:34:51.477
He sees that Muse's
not concentrating...

1355
01:34:51.728 --> 01:34:53.313
...in a world of his own.

1356
01:34:53.521 --> 01:34:55.231
So he has a chance.

1357
01:34:58.401 --> 01:35:01.321
One chance.
The chance he'd been waiting for.

1358
01:35:20.256 --> 01:35:22.759
Saltwater would be good for your foot.

1359
01:35:26.888 --> 01:35:28.348
He got out!

1360
01:35:28.514 --> 01:35:31.142
Turn the boat around!

1361
01:35:31.309 --> 01:35:32.936
Bilal. you idiot!

1362
01:35:33.770 --> 01:35:36.397
They must have been
desperate moments. swimming...

1363
01:35:38.107 --> 01:35:44.197
...seeing the U.S. Navy ships
just across the ocean.

1364
01:35:45.365 --> 01:35:48.409
Unbeknownst to him. of course.
the SEALs are inbound...

1365
01:35:48.660 --> 01:35:49.911
...on the other side.

1366
01:35:50.870 --> 01:35:52.247
Now Najee is awake.

1367
01:35:53.665 --> 01:35:55.541
The pirates try to turn.

1368
01:35:56.417 --> 01:35:57.710
Captain's in Combat.

1369
01:35:57.877 --> 01:36:00.380
Cap. We got two in the water.
Two in the water.

1370
01:36:00.588 --> 01:36:03.049
Starboard side. I see them both.

1371
01:36:03.549 --> 01:36:04.717
Two guys in the water.

1372
01:36:05.969 --> 01:36:08.805
Castellano is brought up to the bridge.

1373
01:36:09.514 --> 01:36:11.307
But the problem is...

1374
01:36:12.183 --> 01:36:16.145
...they're in no position to know who's in
the water and who's not. Is that Phillips?

1375
01:36:16.354 --> 01:36:20.608
Is that Phillips or is that just
two pirates? If they open fire...

1376
01:36:23.236 --> 01:36:25.655
...they might kill Phillips.
so they can't shoot.

1377
01:36:28.658 --> 01:36:32.120
So now we've got simultaneous action.

1378
01:36:33.079 --> 01:36:37.292
Which. I think. any filmmaker
will tell you is always the...

1379
01:36:37.709 --> 01:36:40.545
The thing you're trying to find
if you can really...

1380
01:36:40.920 --> 01:36:44.757
If you can get simultaneous action
occurring and it feels natural...

1381
01:36:45.425 --> 01:36:47.719
...then you really can drive a sequence.

1382
01:36:53.641 --> 01:36:57.186
We shot these pieces
in the tank at Malta.

1383
01:36:57.687 --> 01:37:00.064
In fact. when we started the film.
I thought--

1384
01:37:00.231 --> 01:37:04.861
When we initially began discussing the
film. I thought we'd shoot a lot of it...

1385
01:37:05.069 --> 01:37:07.447
...in the deep-water tanks.
But as it turned out...

1386
01:37:07.613 --> 01:37:11.451
...I think we did two nights. two
short nights. just for this one sequence.

1387
01:37:12.285 --> 01:37:15.788
The swimming under the lifeboat.

1388
01:37:15.997 --> 01:37:17.832
The rest of it was done in the ocean.

1389
01:37:18.666 --> 01:37:22.045
- Can't tell who's in the water.
- No clear shot at the Tangos.

1390
01:37:22.211 --> 01:37:24.756
Nobody shoots
unless there's a clear shot.

1391
01:37:24.964 --> 01:37:26.341
Where is he?

1392
01:37:32.430 --> 01:37:34.432
Here he is! Here he is!

1393
01:37:41.147 --> 01:37:44.067
Phillips in a desperate situation here.

1394
01:37:45.068 --> 01:37:46.110
Of course...

1395
01:37:46.652 --> 01:37:49.030
...the Navy are lighting the sky up...

1396
01:37:49.447 --> 01:37:51.699
...when. in fact.
what he wants is darkness.

1397
01:37:53.826 --> 01:37:58.289
But the truth is.
the distance to the warships was too far.

1398
01:38:00.833 --> 01:38:03.378
Muse was able to jump in and...

1399
01:38:04.629 --> 01:38:05.671
Help!

1400
01:38:05.963 --> 01:38:08.591
And no matter
how hard he tried to escape...

1401
01:38:09.258 --> 01:38:11.719
...the truth is.
he wasn't going anywhere.

1402
01:38:15.681 --> 01:38:17.016
All right!

1403
01:38:17.225 --> 01:38:18.309
- Come!
- All right!

1404
01:38:19.519 --> 01:38:21.187
- Come! Forward!
- All right!

1405
01:38:21.354 --> 01:38:23.356
Got him.

1406
01:38:23.523 --> 01:38:24.941
Come!

1407
01:38:25.108 --> 01:38:27.568
Okay. okay.

1408
01:38:29.529 --> 01:38:32.448
Go in. Irish! Go! Go. Irish!

1409
01:38:33.366 --> 01:38:36.077
Sir. the SEALs are coming aboard.

1410
01:38:36.911 --> 01:38:38.788
<i>Prepare to board the SEALs.</i>

1411
01:38:40.706 --> 01:38:43.334
Trying to create
connectivity with Castellano.

1412
01:38:44.460 --> 01:38:47.922
SEALs are almost aboard. he's really
only got one more throw of the dice...

1413
01:38:48.089 --> 01:38:50.591
...Castellano.
if he's gonna resolve this thing.

1414
01:38:54.262 --> 01:38:57.140
And also. of course. they knew...

1415
01:38:57.723 --> 01:39:00.726
...that Phillips was gonna be beaten
when he got back...

1416
01:39:01.602 --> 01:39:02.645
...in the lifeboat.

1417
01:39:02.812 --> 01:39:04.772
Waiting for you on the bridge. sir.

1418
01:39:12.530 --> 01:39:14.073
Not today!

1419
01:39:14.240 --> 01:39:15.491
Stop him!

1420
01:39:20.621 --> 01:39:22.707
That's enough!

1421
01:39:25.626 --> 01:39:28.963
I think the score is quite brilliant here.
the way you get that...

1422
01:39:31.841 --> 01:39:33.301
...progression of percussion.

1423
01:39:34.760 --> 01:39:37.597
Those descending cello lines...

1424
01:39:37.805 --> 01:39:40.099
...and the high-string pieces.

1425
01:39:40.641 --> 01:39:43.060
There's a sort of a terrible beauty in it.

1426
01:39:48.232 --> 01:39:50.860
<i>Bainbridge</i> to lifeboat.
you must surrender.

1427
01:39:51.027 --> 01:39:53.154
<i>You will not be permitted to go further.</i>

1428
01:39:53.321 --> 01:39:55.156
It's a helicopter!

1429
01:39:55.656 --> 01:39:58.618
So Castellano plays his last card.

1430
01:40:01.787 --> 01:40:04.040
Alabama <i>lifeboat. respond.</i>

1431
01:40:04.207 --> 01:40:05.708
Hurry! Go!

1432
01:40:05.875 --> 01:40:06.959
I'm trying.

1433
01:40:11.631 --> 01:40:12.798
Go!

1434
01:40:12.965 --> 01:40:16.427
<i>You have a choice to make. captain.
Surrender now and this ends peacefully.</i>

1435
01:40:16.594 --> 01:40:18.721
Panic in the desperation...

1436
01:40:19.555 --> 01:40:21.474
...inside that lifeboat.

1437
01:40:22.308 --> 01:40:24.435
That was amazing acting. really.

1438
01:40:24.936 --> 01:40:26.354
Very. very real.

1439
01:40:27.563 --> 01:40:31.400
It's easy to make a noise.
easy to make a commotion.

1440
01:40:31.609 --> 01:40:35.238
What's really hard when you're
a group of actors...

1441
01:40:35.446 --> 01:40:40.701
...is to create real rising and falling
tension and real detail...

1442
01:40:40.910 --> 01:40:43.913
...so you understand each character.
what each character's doing.

1443
01:40:44.121 --> 01:40:45.164
Fashioning moments...

1444
01:40:45.331 --> 01:40:48.876
...dramatic moments along the way
that have got proper shape...

1445
01:40:49.085 --> 01:40:51.754
...so that you invest in the experience.

1446
01:40:54.340 --> 01:40:55.591
Go!

1447
01:40:56.425 --> 01:40:58.219
Go!

1448
01:40:58.427 --> 01:41:00.304
Up ladder.

1449
01:41:03.349 --> 01:41:04.517
Make a hole.

1450
01:41:05.685 --> 01:41:10.856
The music's alternately
twisting and turning...

1451
01:41:11.732 --> 01:41:13.985
...as the tension ratchets up.

1452
01:41:14.694 --> 01:41:17.238
<i>Target in the hatch.
This is</i> Bainbridge <i>out.</i>

1453
01:41:17.947 --> 01:41:20.074
They're holding a gun to Phillips' head.

1454
01:41:20.241 --> 01:41:23.661
He's kind of yelling
and waving his pistol back and forth.

1455
01:41:26.122 --> 01:41:30.334
I kill him! I kill him! Now! I kill him!

1456
01:41:33.421 --> 01:41:35.131
We got shots fired. captain.

1457
01:41:35.298 --> 01:41:37.466
- How many shots?
- Who fired? Who fired?

1458
01:41:37.633 --> 01:41:39.594
We're losing this.

1459
01:41:43.306 --> 01:41:46.517
That's the bridge of the
<i>USS Truxtun.</i> there...

1460
01:41:46.767 --> 01:41:50.438
...with its full complement
of men and women.

1461
01:41:53.399 --> 01:41:57.820
Without them. this would never have had
the reality that it does as a sequence.

1462
01:41:58.237 --> 01:42:00.740
Give me the radio.

1463
01:42:01.824 --> 01:42:06.120
The helicopter is coming back.

1464
01:42:07.204 --> 01:42:11.334
Earlier on. you'll remember we had
the scene where Muse tells Phillips:

1465
01:42:12.376 --> 01:42:13.919
"We're just fishermen."

1466
01:42:16.380 --> 01:42:19.258
This is a very important moment
when Phillips recalls that.

1467
01:42:20.217 --> 01:42:23.220
And throws it back in his face
and it lands with Muse.

1468
01:42:24.555 --> 01:42:27.266
Talk. Talk.

1469
01:42:27.433 --> 01:42:32.730
They got a gun to my throat. and they're
gonna use a survival suit as a body bag.

1470
01:42:38.527 --> 01:42:41.238
You're not just a fisherman.

1471
01:42:41.906 --> 01:42:44.492
You're not just a fisherman.

1472
01:42:48.287 --> 01:42:50.790
<i>Men of the</i> Alabama <i>lifeboat</i>--

1473
01:42:50.956 --> 01:42:54.335
That's a magnificent moment
between the two of them.

1474
01:42:55.419 --> 01:42:58.464
The battle of wills
has just taken another turn.

1475
01:43:02.510 --> 01:43:03.636
Who is this?

1476
01:43:03.803 --> 01:43:06.972
I'm the negotiator.
I'm authorised to negotiate with you.

1477
01:43:07.181 --> 01:43:11.560
And then
the SEAL commander speaks.

1478
01:43:11.769 --> 01:43:14.689
And continuing that theme...

1479
01:43:14.897 --> 01:43:18.901
...of everybody telling lies
to everybody else.

1480
01:43:19.235 --> 01:43:21.654
He tells Muse
he's gonna do a deal with him.

1481
01:43:21.862 --> 01:43:23.989
Muse will get his money.

1482
01:43:25.408 --> 01:43:30.246
No one in this film speaks the truth
to each other.

1483
01:43:30.746 --> 01:43:32.123
Or very rarely.

1484
01:43:32.331 --> 01:43:34.375
We spoke with the elders of your tribe.

1485
01:43:34.542 --> 01:43:38.379
They are coming here to negotiate a deal.
an exchange.

1486
01:43:38.587 --> 01:43:42.466
<i>We get our man. you get your money.
But this has to be done in confidence.</i>

1487
01:43:42.633 --> 01:43:46.137
<i>We don't want anyone to see
the exchange. Neither do the elders.</i>

1488
01:43:46.303 --> 01:43:47.430
It's a lie.

1489
01:43:47.596 --> 01:43:50.766
You're low on fuel.
We got some weather coming in...

1490
01:43:50.933 --> 01:43:54.353
...so I'm suggesting that we tow you out
to the exchange point.

1491
01:43:54.520 --> 01:43:58.607
The difference. I think. between Max
playing the SEAL commander...

1492
01:43:58.816 --> 01:44:02.194
...and Yul playing Captain Castellano:
The way they framed...

1493
01:44:02.403 --> 01:44:05.614
...the different sides
of the military response.

1494
01:44:05.990 --> 01:44:07.950
The accuracy
with which they framed them...

1495
01:44:08.159 --> 01:44:10.953
...and the conviction
with which they played them...

1496
01:44:11.162 --> 01:44:13.831
...was quite remarkable. I think.

1497
01:44:14.749 --> 01:44:17.418
They made those parts
really. really play.

1498
01:44:17.626 --> 01:44:19.503
It's an ambush.

1499
01:44:19.712 --> 01:44:23.632
And equally. in this scene
the way Muse and Najee...

1500
01:44:24.592 --> 01:44:28.220
...frame up their differences.

1501
01:44:41.066 --> 01:44:43.152
Filming this last sequence...

1502
01:44:43.360 --> 01:44:46.447
...was probably
the biggest challenge of the film.

1503
01:44:46.781 --> 01:44:48.699
We didn't have a lot of time.

1504
01:44:48.908 --> 01:44:50.701
Keep me posted on status.

1505
01:44:52.077 --> 01:44:53.829
The Navy provided us
with these ships.

1506
01:44:54.497 --> 01:44:58.167
And we had them
for a very short amount of time.

1507
01:44:58.375 --> 01:45:04.590
And we had to execute
a very complicated...

1508
01:45:05.966 --> 01:45:08.511
A multifaceted action sequence...

1509
01:45:08.719 --> 01:45:14.016
...involving four vessels
and three or four helicopters at night.

1510
01:45:16.519 --> 01:45:18.395
At high speed...

1511
01:45:18.604 --> 01:45:20.147
...with a lot of safety issues...

1512
01:45:20.648 --> 01:45:23.567
...and a lot of coordination issues.

1513
01:45:23.859 --> 01:45:27.446
And it took
a remarkable amount of planning.

1514
01:45:27.655 --> 01:45:31.325
And we were very lucky.

1515
01:45:31.534 --> 01:45:34.245
Which is something
that every director needs...

1516
01:45:34.453 --> 01:45:36.664
...shooting a scene like this.

1517
01:45:42.378 --> 01:45:45.923
Once again.
you need to sell the geography. always.

1518
01:45:46.924 --> 01:45:49.093
Don't let anyone in.

1519
01:45:53.389 --> 01:45:56.892
I was saying earlier. one of
the interesting things about the piece...

1520
01:45:57.101 --> 01:46:03.065
...is the way that characters very rarely
speak the truth to each other.

1521
01:46:04.942 --> 01:46:06.986
Apart from in this scene.

1522
01:46:08.195 --> 01:46:12.992
Which is obviously the culmination
of the relationship...

1523
01:46:13.200 --> 01:46:14.535
...between Muse and Phillips.

1524
01:46:17.288 --> 01:46:19.331
I go Navy ship...

1525
01:46:20.791 --> 01:46:22.543
...get dollars...

1526
01:46:23.961 --> 01:46:24.962
...you go home.

1527
01:46:25.129 --> 01:46:27.131
It starts conventionally.

1528
01:46:27.339 --> 01:46:31.135
How many times have we heard Muse
say. "Everything's gonna be okay"?

1529
01:46:31.927 --> 01:46:38.309
But then it takes a turn into the truthful.

1530
01:46:38.475 --> 01:46:40.144
- -Ransom...

1531
01:46:42.479 --> 01:46:44.315
...nobody get hurt.

1532
01:46:44.481 --> 01:46:48.652
You had $30.000
and a way to Somalia.

1533
01:46:50.988 --> 01:46:52.448
It wasn't enough?

1534
01:46:55.159 --> 01:46:57.202
I got bosses.

1535
01:46:57.870 --> 01:46:59.747
They got rules.

1536
01:46:59.914 --> 01:47:02.249
We all got bosses.

1537
01:47:07.338 --> 01:47:10.341
There's gotta be something
other than being a fisherman...

1538
01:47:10.507 --> 01:47:12.301
...and kidnapping people.

1539
01:47:15.387 --> 01:47:17.640
Maybe in America. Irish.

1540
01:47:18.307 --> 01:47:20.225
Maybe in America.

1541
01:47:25.397 --> 01:47:27.399
<i>Alabama</i> lifeboat. this is the U.S. Navy.

1542
01:47:27.566 --> 01:47:28.984
Magnificent scene.

1543
01:47:30.611 --> 01:47:35.783
I remember reading those two lines
in Billy's first draft.

1544
01:47:36.200 --> 01:47:38.494
And thinking.
"Right there. that's the film."

1545
01:47:38.702 --> 01:47:41.413
And in many ways. the film is all...

1546
01:47:41.580 --> 01:47:44.458
...trying to get to that place
in a way that's believable...

1547
01:47:44.667 --> 01:47:48.212
...so that that conversation
feels believable...

1548
01:47:48.420 --> 01:47:50.339
...between those two characters.

1549
01:47:50.547 --> 01:47:51.882
Without sentimentality...

1550
01:47:52.091 --> 01:47:55.094
...without creating moral equivalents.

1551
01:47:55.594 --> 01:48:01.475
Without suggesting in any way
that Phillips sympathises with Muse...

1552
01:48:01.684 --> 01:48:03.310
...because he doesn't.

1553
01:48:04.103 --> 01:48:08.524
But so you understand both characters.

1554
01:48:10.651 --> 01:48:15.739
And when you've had that moment.
you're ready. then. for the endgame.

1555
01:48:15.948 --> 01:48:18.367
Be advised.
I have eyes on the package.

1556
01:48:18.575 --> 01:48:21.286
And again. same point as earlier.

1557
01:48:21.495 --> 01:48:25.499
You've got to take the time in a sequence
to set up the rules of the sequence.

1558
01:48:25.708 --> 01:48:27.835
Who knows what?

1559
01:48:28.043 --> 01:48:31.422
Who's doing what? Who's in control?
What are the communication systems?

1560
01:48:33.215 --> 01:48:36.552
Put this on. captain.
We need to keep you healthy.

1561
01:48:36.802 --> 01:48:38.595
All the time. you've gotta--

1562
01:48:38.804 --> 01:48:44.393
You must never compromise
the accuracy...

1563
01:48:44.601 --> 01:48:47.855
...and the time you spend
setting things up.

1564
01:48:48.564 --> 01:48:50.774
The more you set up.
the more you can pay off.

1565
01:48:52.776 --> 01:48:54.820
Inside. Go.

1566
01:48:55.446 --> 01:48:56.488
Go.

1567
01:48:56.697 --> 01:49:00.200
- Where are the elders?
- The elders are being flown in.

1568
01:49:01.076 --> 01:49:03.704
Put the gun inside.
We'll take you to your elders.

1569
01:49:03.871 --> 01:49:05.581
Anything happen. he die.

1570
01:49:05.748 --> 01:49:08.667
I give you my word.
Everything will be fine.

1571
01:49:08.834 --> 01:49:11.045
Put the gun down.

1572
01:49:11.211 --> 01:49:12.463
Gun down.

1573
01:49:14.131 --> 01:49:15.507
Wait.

1574
01:49:18.969 --> 01:49:20.554
These guys were all ex-military.

1575
01:49:20.763 --> 01:49:23.223
And they were able
to bring their training to bear.

1576
01:49:23.432 --> 01:49:26.685
We got you. Come on.
Nice and easy. Okay.

1577
01:49:27.603 --> 01:49:31.273
I think you feel. when you watch them.
that they know what they're doing.

1578
01:49:34.610 --> 01:49:36.737
Captain. it'll be over soon. Hang tough.

1579
01:49:36.904 --> 01:49:40.240
Stay in the same seat
you've been sitting in.

1580
01:49:40.532 --> 01:49:43.243
It's funny.
even just watching this now...

1581
01:49:43.452 --> 01:49:46.497
...in a studio. I can feel my palms...

1582
01:49:46.705 --> 01:49:49.041
...starting to sweat a bit.

1583
01:49:49.208 --> 01:49:50.834
Stern seas.

1584
01:49:51.043 --> 01:49:54.338
And that's
because you're responding...

1585
01:49:55.089 --> 01:49:56.423
...to the human situation.

1586
01:49:56.632 --> 01:50:01.303
To the insight that great actors
give you into a human situation.

1587
01:50:02.304 --> 01:50:03.764
You become involved.

1588
01:50:03.972 --> 01:50:05.432
You become truly involved.

1589
01:50:05.599 --> 01:50:08.894
- TAO. initiate high-speed manoeuvre.
- Aye. sir.

1590
01:50:10.729 --> 01:50:13.816
<i>Halyburton. Boxer.</i> This is <i>Bainbridge.</i>

1591
01:50:13.982 --> 01:50:16.068
<i>Commence high-speed manoeuvres.
Over.</i>

1592
01:50:18.362 --> 01:50:20.697
Cause and effect...

1593
01:50:20.906 --> 01:50:23.075
...character development...

1594
01:50:23.283 --> 01:50:26.036
...architecture. control of pace.

1595
01:50:29.331 --> 01:50:31.708
Come up this way. Up this way.

1596
01:50:32.709 --> 01:50:36.755
Chris Rouse and I watched this
and worked it for weeks.

1597
01:50:38.507 --> 01:50:44.304
But he has a wonderful eye
for the architecture of these sequences.

1598
01:50:44.513 --> 01:50:47.141
What weight to give each side.

1599
01:50:47.808 --> 01:50:48.976
Stand over here.

1600
01:50:51.145 --> 01:50:53.272
As you move
from environment to environment...

1601
01:50:53.480 --> 01:50:54.857
...you need to be specific.

1602
01:50:56.150 --> 01:50:58.569
From darkness to light.

1603
01:50:58.861 --> 01:51:02.072
You know.
light can be as disorientating as dark.

1604
01:51:02.239 --> 01:51:04.867
Relax. We're gonna take care of you.

1605
01:51:06.201 --> 01:51:10.455
And now you're watching a man
who realises he's being lied to.

1606
01:51:10.998 --> 01:51:12.875
But again. he doesn't quite know how.

1607
01:51:13.083 --> 01:51:14.960
He doesn't know
what he can do about it.

1608
01:51:23.552 --> 01:51:27.097
Your captain knows what he's doing.
You're gonna get your money now.

1609
01:51:40.777 --> 01:51:44.781
Likewise.
all these guys are ex-military.

1610
01:51:44.990 --> 01:51:46.533
What's going on?

1611
01:51:46.742 --> 01:51:48.160
And I think. again...

1612
01:51:49.912 --> 01:51:55.000
...it's much better to get
former military professionals to act...

1613
01:51:55.209 --> 01:51:57.920
...than it is to get actors
to be military professionals...

1614
01:51:58.128 --> 01:51:59.421
...in my experience.

1615
01:51:59.630 --> 01:52:02.341
We're going to initiate the tow.

1616
01:52:02.507 --> 01:52:05.510
<i>I repeat.
we are going to initiate the tow.</i>

1617
01:52:05.677 --> 01:52:09.765
You need to tell your driver
that he needs to stay in his seat...

1618
01:52:09.932 --> 01:52:12.100
<i>...and continue steering.</i>

1619
01:52:29.868 --> 01:52:34.623
Music takes a turn. obviously.
at this point. You get a heartbeat.

1620
01:52:38.001 --> 01:52:39.336
This thing is building now.

1621
01:52:41.505 --> 01:52:44.258
Alfa team is green at this time.
One green. two red.

1622
01:52:45.259 --> 01:52:49.263
A lot of the musical pieces
that have been put in place earlier...

1623
01:52:49.471 --> 01:52:52.266
...now start to come together.

1624
01:52:52.474 --> 01:52:57.938
The brass is starting to stretch
and twist.

1625
01:53:00.691 --> 01:53:03.610
The pulse has become a heartbeat.

1626
01:53:11.827 --> 01:53:15.330
- Hey. Hey.
- I'm putting on the shirt like they said.

1627
01:53:16.999 --> 01:53:19.584
If he moves again. shoot him.

1628
01:53:19.751 --> 01:53:21.753
Sir. the pirates have just issued a threat.

1629
01:53:21.920 --> 01:53:24.006
One of the extraordinary things...

1630
01:53:24.172 --> 01:53:28.260
...about Tom's performance.
I think in this film. is that he...

1631
01:53:30.262 --> 01:53:32.889
...takes pieces of doubt and fear...

1632
01:53:33.098 --> 01:53:34.850
...and hopelessness...

1633
01:53:35.058 --> 01:53:38.228
...and yet he manages
to fashion out of them...

1634
01:53:38.437 --> 01:53:41.481
...a story of endurance.

1635
01:53:42.983 --> 01:53:45.944
It's almost counter intuitive. really.

1636
01:53:47.487 --> 01:53:49.031
He's not playing the hero.

1637
01:53:49.239 --> 01:53:52.075
On the contrary.
he's playing the reality of the situation...

1638
01:53:52.284 --> 01:53:57.122
...at every step of the way with accuracy
and restraint. self-discipline.

1639
01:53:57.331 --> 01:53:58.790
And so...

1640
01:54:00.208 --> 01:54:05.339
...in an era. I think. cinematically
dominated by superheroes...

1641
01:54:05.547 --> 01:54:10.177
...he's always chosen--
And dared. I think.

1642
01:54:10.385 --> 01:54:12.637
- -To play the ordinary man.

1643
01:54:12.846 --> 01:54:14.348
And that takes--

1644
01:54:14.556 --> 01:54:16.433
You have to accept restrictions.

1645
01:54:16.641 --> 01:54:20.479
Restrictions on who you are.
restrictions on the powers that you have.

1646
01:54:20.687 --> 01:54:22.773
The behaviours that you can exhibit.

1647
01:54:22.981 --> 01:54:28.570
You can't just. you know. rely
on some special power that you have.

1648
01:54:28.779 --> 01:54:31.031
You're just an ordinary person.

1649
01:54:31.239 --> 01:54:32.783
And yet out of that...

1650
01:54:34.201 --> 01:54:38.413
...slowly but surely.
you feel this deep reservoir...

1651
01:54:38.622 --> 01:54:42.918
...of humanity underneath.
and he's done it time and again.

1652
01:54:43.126 --> 01:54:48.382
And I think never better than in this--
The end of this film.

1653
01:54:48.548 --> 01:54:51.426
American ship. answer me.

1654
01:54:51.927 --> 01:54:56.306
You. I think. literally do feel
you're with him...

1655
01:54:56.515 --> 01:54:59.559
...in this unfolding situation.

1656
01:55:01.269 --> 01:55:03.438
As the sympathies twist and turn.

1657
01:55:03.647 --> 01:55:08.276
Do we--? Do we want them
to open fire or don't we?

1658
01:55:10.278 --> 01:55:15.242
What's gonna stand the best?

1659
01:55:15.450 --> 01:55:19.913
What's gonna give the best chance
of a successful outcome?

1660
01:55:20.288 --> 01:55:22.916
That's the question you're asking
as an audience.

1661
01:55:29.172 --> 01:55:33.552
And always that thin fragile line
that connects the lifeboat.

1662
01:55:33.760 --> 01:55:36.346
Irish. Irish. What you doing?

1663
01:55:37.514 --> 01:55:38.557
What you doing?

1664
01:55:42.811 --> 01:55:44.020
We know what he's doing.

1665
01:55:45.063 --> 01:55:47.482
Although it's never spoken.

1666
01:55:50.235 --> 01:55:53.071
We're doing what any of us would do
in this situation.

1667
01:55:53.280 --> 01:55:58.410
If you knew some violent endgame...

1668
01:55:58.618 --> 01:56:01.788
...was about to play out
in which you might or might not live...

1669
01:56:03.540 --> 01:56:05.167
...who would you be thinking about?

1670
01:56:05.333 --> 01:56:06.334
Give me a distance.

1671
01:56:07.043 --> 01:56:09.463
Two twenty. Still 129 out.

1672
01:56:16.136 --> 01:56:17.846
Stop writing. Irish.

1673
01:56:18.638 --> 01:56:21.391
If he sees you. he kill me and you both.

1674
01:56:22.851 --> 01:56:26.480
Those breathing chords. brass chords.

1675
01:56:27.230 --> 01:56:28.899
<i>U.S. Navy. answer!</i>

1676
01:56:30.817 --> 01:56:32.444
Anxious.

1677
01:56:33.445 --> 01:56:36.615
I want to speak with him!

1678
01:56:36.781 --> 01:56:37.824
Alfa and Charlie teams green.

1679
01:56:37.991 --> 01:56:39.910
They're saying. "Wake up."

1680
01:56:41.828 --> 01:56:45.916
And they're slowing rising
and building.

1681
01:56:47.542 --> 01:56:49.503
Where are the elders?

1682
01:56:51.213 --> 01:56:52.464
Where are elders?

1683
01:56:54.591 --> 01:56:57.260
American ship. answer!

1684
01:56:57.427 --> 01:56:59.346
Hey.

1685
01:56:59.513 --> 01:57:01.306
Hey! What is this?

1686
01:57:01.515 --> 01:57:05.268
Subterranean movement
giving you unease.

1687
01:57:06.394 --> 01:57:09.272
They've got something going on.
I think it's a fight.

1688
01:57:10.106 --> 01:57:15.153
Well. we've waited for this throw-down
since the earliest moment.

1689
01:57:18.114 --> 01:57:20.742
Phillips himself said
he always thought...

1690
01:57:22.035 --> 01:57:25.413
...that he'd get a bullet in the head
from the big. tall guy.

1691
01:57:26.665 --> 01:57:28.959
He was the one
he was most frightened of.

1692
01:57:30.377 --> 01:57:31.670
Stop Irish! Stop Irish!

1693
01:57:31.836 --> 01:57:34.005
Bring the rope!

1694
01:57:35.507 --> 01:57:38.093
Alfa and Charlie are red.
We are three red.

1695
01:57:38.260 --> 01:57:40.428
<i>Alabama</i> lifeboat. this is the negotiator.

1696
01:57:40.595 --> 01:57:43.056
If you harm the hostage.
we do not have a deal.

1697
01:57:43.807 --> 01:57:45.308
<i>Do you copy?</i>

1698
01:57:49.145 --> 01:57:50.647
Tie him!

1699
01:57:52.274 --> 01:57:57.195
The interesting situation
is that with Muse off the lifeboat...

1700
01:57:57.404 --> 01:58:01.491
...command and control
really breaks down.

1701
01:58:11.042 --> 01:58:12.836
What are you doing?

1702
01:58:15.213 --> 01:58:17.757
Captain Phillips. can you hear me?

1703
01:58:18.174 --> 01:58:21.761
- Captain Phillips. can you hear me?
- He's screaming. sir.

1704
01:58:22.721 --> 01:58:27.475
- One fifty-five. They're 64 metres out.
- One fifty-five. check. Speed up the tow.

1705
01:58:30.937 --> 01:58:35.400
Now we are moving
towards the conclusion.

1706
01:58:44.534 --> 01:58:47.370
The situation is running out of control.

1707
01:58:49.039 --> 01:58:50.707
Shut up!

1708
01:58:51.583 --> 01:58:54.210
Get a blindfold!

1709
01:58:57.297 --> 01:58:59.466
Can you see this?

1710
01:59:00.091 --> 01:59:01.134
Can you see it?

1711
01:59:01.968 --> 01:59:04.804
Let's reacquire targets.
weapons release on my command.

1712
01:59:05.013 --> 01:59:07.807
One thirty-five metres.
That's 44 out from optimal.

1713
01:59:07.974 --> 01:59:10.894
Alfa green.
Bravo and Charlie are still red. Two red.

1714
01:59:11.353 --> 01:59:13.396
Blindfold him.

1715
01:59:17.067 --> 01:59:21.112
Kid. just put your hands up.
You're just a kid.

1716
01:59:21.279 --> 01:59:27.369
Now all that preparatory work
between Phillips and Bilal...

1717
01:59:28.036 --> 01:59:31.998
...pays off in this scene. I think.
because we know this character.

1718
01:59:32.207 --> 01:59:34.668
We know the young kid.
We know who he is.

1719
01:59:34.918 --> 01:59:36.544
Andrea. I love you.

1720
01:59:37.504 --> 01:59:38.755
I love you. Ange.

1721
01:59:39.547 --> 01:59:40.757
Honey. I love you.

1722
01:59:42.509 --> 01:59:44.344
I love you. Danny. I'm sorry.

1723
01:59:44.511 --> 01:59:48.973
I'm sorry I'm here
and not there with you.

1724
01:59:49.432 --> 01:59:53.228
<i>Can anybody hear this?
I can't stand this anymore.</i>

1725
01:59:53.436 --> 01:59:55.980
One thirty metres.
That's 39 out from optimal.

1726
01:59:56.147 --> 01:59:58.191
Two red. No shot. Still at two red.

1727
01:59:58.358 --> 02:00:02.112
I need sights on targets.
I need three targets green.

1728
02:00:05.573 --> 02:00:07.617
Don't kill him!

1729
02:00:07.784 --> 02:00:09.828
The elders are coming.

1730
02:00:09.994 --> 02:00:11.371
We will get our money.

1731
02:00:11.538 --> 02:00:13.957
You are both idiots.

1732
02:00:14.124 --> 02:00:15.709
No one is coming.

1733
02:00:19.879 --> 02:00:23.633
When you make a film
and you direct a film...

1734
02:00:25.385 --> 02:00:28.763
...when you look at it back--
At least I find. anyway.

1735
02:00:28.930 --> 02:00:32.392
- -Often my overwhelming feeling...

1736
02:00:32.600 --> 02:00:37.021
...is of the mastery of all that work...

1737
02:00:37.981 --> 02:00:42.527
...that you've been able to be around.

1738
02:00:42.861 --> 02:00:44.028
It's almost like:

1739
02:00:44.946 --> 02:00:48.032
Isn't that wonderfully shot?
Isn't that wonderfully performed?

1740
02:00:48.241 --> 02:00:50.368
Isn't Tom magnificent there?

1741
02:00:50.577 --> 02:00:53.997
Isn't that group environment
in the control room magnificent?

1742
02:00:54.205 --> 02:00:55.707
Isn't this beautifully edited?

1743
02:00:56.166 --> 02:01:00.587
As a director. you're a jack of all trades
but a master of none.

1744
02:01:00.795 --> 02:01:03.214
But you're surrounded by masters.

1745
02:01:03.423 --> 02:01:09.220
And it leaves you with a feeling
of tremendous humility. I think...

1746
02:01:09.471 --> 02:01:15.435
...that your film has been made
by so many hands.

1747
02:01:17.270 --> 02:01:22.734
And that it can end up
by fashioning this moment.

1748
02:01:27.822 --> 02:01:29.532
Shock.

1749
02:01:30.575 --> 02:01:32.410
Violence.

1750
02:01:33.203 --> 02:01:35.205
Resolution.

1751
02:01:35.955 --> 02:01:39.292
Safety. Confusion.

1752
02:01:39.793 --> 02:01:41.419
Horror.

1753
02:01:45.882 --> 02:01:50.678
A great. great actor fashioning
a great. great moment in cinema...

1754
02:01:50.887 --> 02:01:52.639
...I think. for me.

1755
02:02:16.579 --> 02:02:19.123
We're gonna get you out of here
and get you home.

1756
02:02:20.625 --> 02:02:25.421
Ending this film was a great challenge.

1757
02:02:25.630 --> 02:02:28.800
There were so many obvious ways
you could end it.

1758
02:02:29.801 --> 02:02:35.098
And however you end it.
you have to resolve your characters.

1759
02:02:36.307 --> 02:02:41.145
As surely as you have to set them up.
you have to resolve them. pay them off.

1760
02:02:43.731 --> 02:02:45.942
Most of all...

1761
02:02:47.694 --> 02:02:50.905
...I wanted it not to feel triumphant.

1762
02:02:52.323 --> 02:02:54.951
I wanted it to feel real.

1763
02:02:56.411 --> 02:02:58.204
This way.

1764
02:03:01.124 --> 02:03:03.293
- Watch your step.
- Step.

1765
02:03:07.255 --> 02:03:09.007
Careful. sir.

1766
02:03:11.676 --> 02:03:15.179
There's something about this story...

1767
02:03:15.638 --> 02:03:20.184
...of four armed. desperate young men
from Somalia attacking a large ship...

1768
02:03:20.393 --> 02:03:22.186
...taking the captain hostage.

1769
02:03:23.146 --> 02:03:28.651
Trying to take him back to Somalia
before anyone can rescue him.

1770
02:03:29.360 --> 02:03:32.864
That speaks to larger forces
in our world. I think.

1771
02:03:34.240 --> 02:03:37.410
And larger challenges that we face.

1772
02:03:37.994 --> 02:03:39.621
It's a crime story. really.

1773
02:03:41.247 --> 02:03:46.252
A story of crime and retribution.
as all great crime stories should be.

1774
02:03:47.879 --> 02:03:53.801
A story from the far edges...

1775
02:03:54.010 --> 02:03:56.596
...the far oceans of the global economy.

1776
02:03:58.473 --> 02:04:02.727
A story about four men locked out...

1777
02:04:03.937 --> 02:04:05.480
...trying to take their prize.

1778
02:04:06.439 --> 02:04:10.234
And what it means to an ordinary man.

1779
02:04:10.526 --> 02:04:13.029
A man a bit like my father.

1780
02:04:13.237 --> 02:04:15.990
A man who'd spent his life at sea.

1781
02:04:16.157 --> 02:04:17.909
Can you talk?

1782
02:04:18.076 --> 02:04:19.911
- Can you tell me what's going on?
- Yeah.

1783
02:04:20.078 --> 02:04:22.288
So when he's finally safe...

1784
02:04:22.497 --> 02:04:24.707
Are you okay?
Because you don't look okay.

1785
02:04:25.541 --> 02:04:29.837
...the shock and the confusion...

1786
02:04:31.506 --> 02:04:33.758
...is our shock and confusion.
I think.

1787
02:04:35.802 --> 02:04:39.305
What do we think
about what we've seen?

1788
02:04:39.514 --> 02:04:42.058
How do we make sense of it?

1789
02:04:42.850 --> 02:04:44.894
The guilty have been punished.

1790
02:04:45.103 --> 02:04:47.563
The innocent man is free.

1791
02:04:48.648 --> 02:04:49.941
The tension is over.

1792
02:04:50.566 --> 02:04:53.903
We're gonna put this on.
get your heart rate and oxygen level...

1793
02:04:54.070 --> 02:04:56.030
- ...make sure you're breathing.
- Okay.

1794
02:04:56.197 --> 02:05:00.159
- I want you to keep doing that. okay?
- Gonna put this on your finger.

1795
02:05:00.326 --> 02:05:02.537
Can you tell me what happened
to your head?

1796
02:05:02.704 --> 02:05:04.372
Put it on your finger.

1797
02:05:05.206 --> 02:05:06.874
They...

1798
02:05:10.253 --> 02:05:14.382
And I think in this scene...

1799
02:05:15.091 --> 02:05:19.053
...Tom explores the reality of that.

1800
02:05:19.220 --> 02:05:21.014
I want you to look at me and breathe.

1801
02:05:21.222 --> 02:05:22.265
- Understand?
- Yeah.

1802
02:05:22.432 --> 02:05:23.725
Okay. all right.

1803
02:05:25.059 --> 02:05:29.689
He dares to explore vulnerability.

1804
02:05:30.940 --> 02:05:32.567
Vulnerability with control.

1805
02:05:32.775 --> 02:05:36.612
Vulnerability with insight.

1806
02:05:38.614 --> 02:05:41.534
The truest power of acting. really.

1807
02:05:42.201 --> 02:05:46.247
To make you feel
that you're really there.

1808
02:05:46.456 --> 02:05:49.959
That you've really lived through it.
That it's meant something to you.

1809
02:05:52.003 --> 02:05:58.426
But that meaning remaining elusive...

1810
02:06:00.178 --> 02:06:04.307
...whilst the personal cost of it
is clear and true.

1811
02:06:04.515 --> 02:06:06.184
That's brilliant acting for me.

1812
02:06:08.061 --> 02:06:09.395
A great way to end. I think.

1813
02:06:09.604 --> 02:06:11.856
The only way. as it turned out.
to end this film.

1814
02:06:12.482 --> 02:06:15.902
You'll be able to call them
as soon as you are taken care of.

1815
02:06:18.196 --> 02:06:20.281
Sir. I need you to breathe. okay?

1816
02:06:20.448 --> 02:06:23.034
You are safe and you are fine.

1817
02:06:23.826 --> 02:06:25.703
It's gonna be okay.

1818
02:06:26.788 --> 02:06:28.998
Everything's gonna be okay.

1819
02:06:29.540 --> 02:06:35.505
That was the question
that was asked in the first scene.

1820
02:06:35.713 --> 02:06:38.549
That everything is gonna be okay.
isn't it?

1821
02:06:38.549 --> 02:07:08.549
<b>Subtitle 
 www.movieddl.me</b>

1822
02:07:32.061 --> 02:07:36.274
The men and women of the <i>Truxtun</i>
were extraordinary...

1823
02:07:36.482 --> 02:07:38.442
...in their commitment to this film.

1824
02:07:38.651 --> 02:07:41.696
You ask them. you meet them.
you explain what you're trying to do.

1825
02:07:41.904 --> 02:07:44.365
And they make a decision.
Sometimes they help.

1826
02:07:44.574 --> 02:07:48.870
They've helped on some films.
They haven't helped on others. It's...

1827
02:07:49.453 --> 02:07:53.249
The good thing is that when they help.
they're with you a hundred percent...

1828
02:07:53.457 --> 02:07:55.626
...as they did in this case.

1829
02:07:58.838 --> 02:08:02.425
Richard Phillips came to the set
a couple of days into the shoot.

1830
02:08:02.633 --> 02:08:08.681
Tom had spent some time with him.
quite a bit of time with him. earlier on.

1831
02:08:10.349 --> 02:08:12.768
He was a very nice man.

1832
02:08:13.352 --> 02:08:16.230
Every inch a Merchant Mariner.

1833
02:08:17.231 --> 02:08:22.862
And one of the nicest things
of the whole experience...

1834
02:08:23.070 --> 02:08:26.449
...was to show him and his wife the film
when it was all over.

1835
02:08:26.657 --> 02:08:32.413
And I remember Ange. his wife.
coming out in floods of tears.

1836
02:08:32.622 --> 02:08:34.999
I think she'd found it
very. very overwhelming...

1837
02:08:35.208 --> 02:08:40.087
...to be taken that close
to the experience.

1838
02:08:40.838 --> 02:08:44.383
Richard is a very phlegmatic man.

1839
02:08:44.592 --> 02:08:47.178
He said. "It's a good movie."
He said:

1840
02:08:47.720 --> 02:08:51.224
"But it's not the same
as having a real gun put at your head."

1841
02:08:54.352 --> 02:08:58.105
I think the more you can involve
military professionals...

1842
02:08:58.314 --> 02:09:00.358
...if your film is set in their world...

1843
02:09:00.566 --> 02:09:04.904
...the better chance you've got
of authenticity.

1844
02:09:05.112 --> 02:09:08.282
And that was certainly the case here.
you know?

1845
02:09:08.491 --> 02:09:12.203
I think anybody who is familiar
with those worlds...

1846
02:09:12.411 --> 02:09:15.748
...would say that this
is a pretty accurate depiction...

1847
02:09:15.957 --> 02:09:19.627
...of how they respond
to these kinds of emergencies.

1848
02:09:22.755 --> 02:09:26.259
When Barry and I
began discussing the movie...

1849
02:09:26.467 --> 02:09:31.180
...we initially thought
we'd go the digital route.

1850
02:09:31.889 --> 02:09:35.935
But in the end.
we knew we would be on water.

1851
02:09:36.143 --> 02:09:41.190
We knew we would be
in a lot of small skiffs.

1852
02:09:41.482 --> 02:09:45.361
And I was worried
we might have technical problems.

1853
02:09:45.611 --> 02:09:50.157
And in the end.
we chose to go back to 35.

1854
02:09:50.366 --> 02:09:55.162
Although some of the stuff in the skiffs
we shot on 16.

1855
02:09:55.371 --> 02:09:59.875
Because you get a bigger lens.
and a lighter weight.

1856
02:10:00.084 --> 02:10:02.670
And it gave us the manoeuvrability
we wanted...

1857
02:10:02.878 --> 02:10:08.426
...in very. very dynamic.
physical. challenging conditions.

1858
02:10:11.387 --> 02:10:13.556
Khat. khat.

1859
02:10:13.764 --> 02:10:17.018
Khat is a plant. It's a leaf.

1860
02:10:17.393 --> 02:10:19.145
And it's a drug.

1861
02:10:19.353 --> 02:10:21.856
It's actually a little bit like a--

1862
02:10:22.064 --> 02:10:25.818
Not as strong.
but going towards like a coca leaf.

1863
02:10:26.027 --> 02:10:32.199
And it's a drug that's ubiquitously used
throughout Somalia...

1864
02:10:32.408 --> 02:10:35.077
...and elsewhere in the Horn of Africa.

1865
02:10:35.286 --> 02:10:39.040
And people who live on the water
particularly use it...

1866
02:10:39.248 --> 02:10:43.961
...because it combats the effects
of seasickness.

1867
02:10:47.173 --> 02:10:48.382
I'm pretty good. actually.

1868
02:10:48.591 --> 02:10:51.135
Tom and I. we were fine.
And. you know. a few of us--

1869
02:10:51.344 --> 02:10:54.055
But some people found it
very challenging.

1870
02:10:54.263 --> 02:10:58.184
But. no. I was all right.
I don't really get seasick. luckily.

1871
02:11:01.187 --> 02:11:05.691
One of the attractions of the film was
working with Tom. from my point of view.

1872
02:11:05.900 --> 02:11:07.651
And he and I knew each other...

1873
02:11:07.860 --> 02:11:10.237
...and we'd talked
about finding something to do.

1874
02:11:10.446 --> 02:11:14.075
So when this came up.
I jumped at it because I thought--

1875
02:11:14.283 --> 02:11:18.496
You know. he was already involved.
But I thought he was perfect for the part.

1876
02:11:18.704 --> 02:11:23.709
And. you know. I wasn't gonna miss
the chance to team up with him.

1877
02:11:23.918 --> 02:11:29.006
Tom's just a wonderful actor
and a total gentleman. you know?

1878
02:11:29.215 --> 02:11:34.178
And he had to put up with a lot
on this film.

1879
02:11:37.181 --> 02:11:39.809
So I just wanna say a big thank you...

1880
02:11:40.017 --> 02:11:44.647
...to everybody
who helped us make this film.

1881
02:11:45.398 --> 02:11:47.566
And there were many of them.

1882
02:11:47.775 --> 02:11:52.613
And this is Paul Greengrass.
signing off...

1883
02:11:52.822 --> 02:11:55.950
...on the director's commentary
for <i>Captain Phillips.</i>
